# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: manufacturing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In the 1980s, 3D printing techniques were considered suitable only for the production of functional or aesthetic prototypes, and a more appropriate term for it at the time was rapid prototyping.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] As of 2019, the precision, repeatability, and material range of 3D printing have increased to the point that some 3D printing processes are considered viable as an industrial-production technology; in this context, the term *additive manufacturing* can be used synonymously with *3D printing*.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] One of the key advantages of 3D printing is the ability to produce very complex shapes or geometries that would be otherwise infeasible to construct by hand, including hollow parts or parts with internal truss structures to reduce weight while creating less material waste.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Fused deposition modeling (FDM), which uses a continuous filament of a thermoplastic material, is the most common 3D printing process in use as of 2020.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The umbrella term *additive manufacturing (AM)* gained popularity in the 2000s, inspired by the theme of material being added together (in any of various ways).
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In contrast, the term *subtractive manufacturing* appeared as a retronym for the large family of machining processes with material *removal* as their common process.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* still referred only to the polymer technologies in most minds, and the term *AM* was more likely to be used in metalworking and end-use part production contexts than among polymer, inkjet, or stereolithography enthusiasts.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Until recently, the term *3D printing* has been associated with machines low in price or capability.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] *3D printing* and *additive manufacturing* reflect that the technologies share the theme of material addition or joining throughout a 3D work envelope under automated control.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Other terms that have been used as synonyms or hypernyms have included *desktop manufacturing*, *rapid manufacturing* (as the logical production-level successor to *rapid prototyping*), and *on-demand manufacturing* (which echoes *on-demand printing* in the 2D sense of *printing*).
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Today, the term *subtractive* has not replaced the term *machining*, instead complementing it when a term that covers any removal method is needed.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Agile tooling is the use of modular means to design tooling that is produced by additive manufacturing or 3D printing methods to enable quick prototyping and responses to tooling and fixture needs.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Agile tooling uses a cost-effective and high-quality method to quickly respond to customer and market needs, and it can be used in hydroforming, stamping, injection molding and other manufacturing processes.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Although the terms 3D printing and additive manufacturing can both be seen as the same thing, some standards organizitons make a distinction between them.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) says that international standards such as IS0/ASTM 52900 define additive manufacturing as the process of building parts from 3D model data and adding material layer by layer.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In comparison, 3D printing is described as creating objects by depositing material through a print head or some variation of a nozzle type of device.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In industrial and technical settings, additive manufacturing is often the preferred term, and 3D printing is used more by the general public.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The general concept of and procedure to be used in 3D-printing was first described by Murray Leinster in his 1945 short story "Things Pass By": "But this constructor is both efficient and flexible.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] I feed magnetronic plastics — the stuff they make houses and ships of nowadays — into this moving arm.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] It makes drawings in the air following drawings it scans with photo-cells.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Jones in his story, "Tools of the Trade", published in the November 1950 issue of *Astounding Science Fiction* magazine.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] He referred to it as a "molecular spray" in that story.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 1971, Johannes F Gottwald patented the Liquid Metal Recorder, U.S. patent 3596285A, a continuous inkjet metal material device to form a removable metal fabrication on a reusable surface for immediate use or salvaged for printing again by remelting.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This appears to be the first patent describing 3D printing with rapid prototyping and controlled on-demand manufacturing of patterns.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Jones laid out the concept of 3D printing in his regular column *Ariadne* in the journal *New Scientist*.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Early additive manufacturing equipment and materials were developed in the 1980s.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In April 1980, Hideo Kodama of Nagoya Municipal Industrial Research Institute invented two additive methods for fabricating three-dimensional plastic models with photo-hardening thermoset polymer, where the UV exposure area is controlled by a mask pattern or a scanning fiber transmitter.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] He filed a patent for this XYZ plotter, which was published on 10 November 1981.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] His research results as journal papers were published in April and November 1981.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] However, there was no reaction to the series of his publications.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] His device was not highly evaluated in the laboratory and his boss did not show any interest.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] His research budget was just 60,000 yen or $545 a year.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Acquiring the patent rights for the XYZ plotter was abandoned, and the project was terminated.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] On 2 July 1984, American entrepreneur Bill Masters filed a patent for his computer automated manufacturing process and system (US 4665492).
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This filing is on record at the USPTO as the first 3D printing patent in history; it was the first of three patents belonging to Masters that laid the foundation for the 3D printing systems used today.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] On 16 July 1984, Alain Le Méhauté, Olivier de Witte, and Jean Claude André filed their patent for the stereolithography process.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The application of the French inventors was abandoned by the French General Electric Company (now Alcatel-Alsthom) and CILAS (The Laser Consortium).
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The claimed reason was "for lack of business perspective".
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Research (later named Howtek, Inc. in February 1984) to develop Pixelmaster, a color inkjet 2D printer using Thermoplastic (hot-melt) plastic ink, which was commercialized in 1986.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A team was put together, 6 members from Exxon Office Systems, Danbury Systems Division, an inkjet printer startup and some members of Howtek, Inc group who became popular figures in the 3D printing industry.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] One Howtek member was Richard Helinski, responsible for patent US5136515A ("Method and Means for constructing three-dimensional articles by particle deposition", application 7 November 1989 granted 4 August 1992).
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] He formed C.A.D-Cast, Inc (later renamed to Visual Impact Corporation (VIC) on 22 August 1991), a New Hampshire company.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The company's prototype VIC 3D printer is available with a video presentation showing a 3D model printed with a single nozzle inkjet.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Another employee, Herbert Menhennett, formed HM Research, a New Hampshire company, in 1991 and introduced the Howtek, Inc, inkjet technology and thermoplastic materials to Royden Sanders of SDI and Bill Masters of Ballistic Particle Manufacturing (BPM), where he worked for a number of years.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Both BPM 3D printers and SPI 3D printers use Howtek, Inc style Inkjets and materials.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] McMahon, who was hired by Howtek, Inc to help develop the inkjet, later worked at Sanders Prototype and now operates Layer Grown Model Technology, a 3D service provider specializing in Howtek single nozzle inkjet and SDI printer support.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] McMahon worked with Steven Zoltan, inventor of the 1972 drop-on-demand inkjet at Exxon and holder of a 1978 patent that expanded the understanding of the single nozzle design inkjets (Alpha jets), to help perfect the Howtek, Inc hot-melt inkjets.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This Howtek hot-melt thermoplastic technology is popular with metal investment casting, especially in the 3D printing jewelry industry.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Royden Sanders licensed the Helinksi patent prior to manufacturing the Modelmaker 6 Pro at Sanders prototype, Inc (SPI) in 1993.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The first customer of the Modelmaker 6Pro was Hitchner Corporations, Metal Casting Technology, Inc in Milford, New Hampshire, a mile from the SDI facility in late 1993–1995 casting golf clubs and auto engine parts.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Hull defined the process as a "system for generating three-dimensional objects by creating a cross-sectional pattern of the object to be formed".
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Hull's contribution was the STL (Stereolithography) file format and the digital slicing and infill strategies common to many processes today.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 1986, Charles "Chuck" Hull was granted a patent for this system, and his company, 3D Systems Corporation was formed and it released the first commercial 3D printer, the SLA-1, later in 1987 or 1988.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The technology used by most 3D printers to date—especially hobbyist and consumer-oriented models—is fused deposition modeling, a special application of plastic extrusion, developed in 1988 by S.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Scott Crump and commercialized by his company Stratasys, which marketed its first FDM machine in 1992.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] AM processes for metal sintering or melting (such as selective laser sintering, direct metal laser sintering, and selective laser melting) usually went by their own individual names in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] However, the automated techniques that *added* metal, which would later be called additive manufacturing, were beginning to challenge that assumption.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] By the mid-1990s, new techniques for material deposition were developed at Stanford and Carnegie Mellon University, including microcasting and sprayed materials.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Sacrificial and support materials had also become more common, enabling new object geometries.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* originally referred to a powder bed process employing standard and custom inkjet print heads, developed at MIT by Emanuel Sachs in 1993 and commercialized by Soligen Technologies, Extrude Hone Corporation, and Z Corporation.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The year 1993 also saw the start of an inkjet 3D printer company initially named Sanders Prototype, Inc and later named Solidscape, introducing a high-precision polymer jet fabrication system with soluble support structures, (categorized as a "dot-on-dot" technique).
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 1995 the Fraunhofer Society developed the selective laser melting process.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In the early 2000s 3D printers were still largely being used just in the manufacturing and research industries, as the technology was still relatively young and was too expensive for most consumers to be able to get their hands on.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The 2000s was when larger scale use of the technology began being seen in industry, most often in the architecture and medical industries, though it was typically used for low accuracy modeling and testing, rather than the production of common manufactured goods or heavy prototyping.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 2005 users began to design and distribute plans for 3D printers that could print around 70% of their own parts, the original plans of which were designed by Adrian Bowyer at the University of Bath in 2004, with the name of the project being RepRap (Replicating Rapid-prototyper).
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2006 the Fab@Home project was started by Evan Malone and Hod Lipson, another project whose purpose was to design a low-cost and open source fabrication system that users could develop on their own and post feedback on, making the project very collaborative.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Much of the software for 3D printing available to the public at the time was open source, and as such was quickly distributed and improved upon by many individual users.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 2009 the Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) printing process patents expired.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This opened the door to a new wave of startup companies, many of which were established by major contributors of these open source initiatives, with the goal of many of them being to start developing commercial FDM 3D printers that were more accessible to the general public.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] As the various additive processes matured, it became clear that soon metal removal would no longer be the only metalworking process done through a tool or head moving through a 3D work envelope, transforming a mass of raw material into a desired shape layer by layer.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The 2010s were the first decade in which metal end-use parts such as engine brackets and large nuts would be grown (either before or instead of machining) in job production rather than obligately being machined from bar stock or plate.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] One place that AM is making a significant inroad is in the aviation industry.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] With nearly 3.8 billion air travelers in 2016, the demand for fuel efficient and easily produced jet engines has never been higher.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] One example of AM integration with aerospace was in 2016 when Airbus delivered the first of GE's LEAP engines.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This engine has integrated 3D-printed fuel nozzles, reducing parts from 20 to 1, a 25% weight reduction, and reduced assembly times.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A fuel nozzle is the perfect inroad for additive manufacturing in a jet engine since it allows for optimized design of the complex internals and it is a low-stress, non-rotating part.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2015, PW delivered their first AM parts in the PurePower PW1500G to Bombardier.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Sticking to low-stress, non-rotating parts, PW selected the compressor stators and synch ring brackets to roll out this new manufacturing technology for the first time.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] While AM is still playing a small role in the total number of parts in the jet engine manufacturing process, the return on investment can already be seen by the reduction in parts, the rapid production capabilities and the "optimized design in terms of performance and cost".
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] As technology matured, several authors began to speculate that 3D printing could aid in sustainable development in the developing world.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 2012, Filabot developed a system for closing the loop with plastic and allows for any FDM or FFF 3D printer to be able to print with a wider range of plastics.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Tentzeris demonstrated the first multi-material, vertically integrated printed electronics additive manufacturing platform (VIPRE) which enabled 3D printing of functional electronics operating up to 40 GHz.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] As the price of printers started to drop people interested in this technology had more access and freedom to make what they wanted.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] As of 2014, the price for commercial printers was still high with the cost being over $2,000.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The term "3D printing" originally referred to a process that deposits a binder material onto a powder bed with inkjet printer heads layer by layer.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] More recently, the popular vernacular has started using the term to encompass a wider variety of additive-manufacturing techniques such as electron-beam additive manufacturing and selective laser melting.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The United States and global technical standards use the official term *additive manufacturing* for this broader sense.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The most commonly used 3D printing process (46% as of 2018) is a material extrusion technique called fused deposition modeling, or FDM.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] While FDM technology was invented after the other two most popular technologies, stereolithography (SLA) and selective laser sintering (SLS), FDM is typically the most inexpensive of the three by a large margin, which lends to the popularity of the process.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] As of 2020, 3D printers have reached the level of quality and price that allows most people to enter the world of 3D printing.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 2020 decent quality printers can be found for less than US$200 for entry-level machines.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] These more affordable printers are usually fused deposition modeling (FDM) printers.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In November 2021 a British patient named Steve Verze received the world's first fully 3D-printed prosthetic eye from the Moorfields Eye Hospital in London.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In April 2024, the world's largest 3D printer, the Factory of the Future 1.0 was revealed at the University of Maine.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] It is able to make objects 96 feet long, or 29 meters.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 2024, researchers used machine learning to improve the construction of synthetic bone and set a record for shock absorption.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In July 2024, researchers published a paper in *Advanced Materials Technologies* describing the development of artificial blood vessels using 3D-printing technology, which are as strong and durable as natural blood vessels.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The process involved using a rotating spindle integrated into a 3D printer to create grafts from a water-based gel, which were then coated in biodegradable polyester molecules.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In October 2025, the North Bristol NHS Trust reported that a UK cyclist named Dave Richards had received a full-face 3D-printed prosthesis, created at the newly opened Bristol 3D Medical Center at North Bristol NHS Trust.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Led by senior reconstructive scientist Amy Davey, the process used advanced scanning and medical-grade resins to replicate his facial features after severe burns.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] It marked a milestone in integrated medical 3D-printing facilities in the UK.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Additive manufacturing or 3D printing has rapidly gained importance in the field of engineering due to its many benefits.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The vision of 3D printing is design freedom, individualization, decentralization and executing processes that were previously impossible through alternative methods.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some of these benefits include enabling faster prototyping, reducing manufacturing costs, increasing product customization, and improving product quality.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Furthermore, the capabilities of 3D printing have extended beyond traditional manufacturing, like lightweight construction, or repair and maintenance with applications in prosthetics, bioprinting, food industry, rocket building, design and art and renewable energy systems.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 3D printing technology can be used to produce battery energy storage systems, which are essential for sustainable energy generation and distribution.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Another benefit of 3D printing is the technology's ability to produce complex geometries with high precision and accuracy.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This is particularly relevant in the field of microwave engineering, where 3D printing can be used to produce components with unique properties that are difficult to achieve using traditional manufacturing methods.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Additive Manufacturing processes generate minimal waste by adding material only where needed, unlike traditional methods that cut away excess material.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This reduces both material costs and environmental impact.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This reduction in waste also lowers energy consumption for material production and disposal, contributing to a smaller carbon footprint.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 3D printable models may be created with a computer-aided design (CAD) package, via a 3D scanner, or by a plain digital camera and photogrammetry software.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 3D printed models created with CAD result in relatively fewer errors than other methods.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Errors in 3D printable models can be identified and corrected before printing.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 3D scanning is a process of collecting digital data on the shape and appearance of a real object, and creating a digital model based on it.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] CAD models can be saved in the stereolithography file format (STL), a de facto CAD file format for additive manufacturing that stores data based on triangulations of the surface of CAD models.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] STL is not tailored for additive manufacturing because it generates large file sizes of topology-optimized parts and lattice structures due to the large number of surfaces involved.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A newer CAD file format, the additive manufacturing file format (AMF), was introduced in 2011 to solve this problem.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] It stores information using curved triangulations.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Before printing a 3D model from an STL file, it must first be examined for errors.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A step in the STL generation known as "repair" fixes such problems in the original model.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Generally, STLs that have been produced from a model obtained through 3D scanning often have more of these errors as 3D scanning is often achieved by point to point acquisition/mapping.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 3D reconstruction often includes errors.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Once completed, the STL file needs to be processed by a piece of software called a "slicer", which converts the model into a series of thin layers and produces a G-code file containing instructions tailored to a specific type of 3D printer.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] For instance FDM printers use FDM file formats.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This G-code file can then be printed with 3D printing client software (which loads the G-code and uses it to instruct the 3D printer during the 3D printing process).
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Printer resolution describes layer thickness and X–Y resolution in dots per inch (dpi) or micrometers (μm).
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Typical layer thickness is around 100 μm (250 DPI), although some machines can print layers as thin as 16 μm (1,600 DPI).
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] X–Y resolution is comparable to that of laser printers.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] For that printer resolution, specifying a mesh resolution of 0.01–0.03 mm and a chord length ≤ 0.016 mm generates an optimal STL output file for a given model input file.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Specifying higher resolution results in larger files without increase in print quality.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Construction of a model with contemporary methods can take anywhere from several hours to several days, depending on the method used and the size and complexity of the model.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Additive systems can typically reduce this time to a few hours, although it varies widely depending on the type of machine used and the size and number of models being produced simultaneously.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Though the printer-produced resolution and surface finish are sufficient for some applications, post-processing and finishing methods allow for benefits such as greater dimensional accuracy, smoother surfaces, and other modifications such as coloration.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The surface finish of a 3D-printed part can improved using subtractive methods such as sanding and bead blasting.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] When smoothing parts that require dimensional accuracy, it is important to take into account the volume of the material being removed.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some printable polymers, such as acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), allow the surface finish to be smoothed and improved using chemical vapor processes based on acetone or similar solvents.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques can benefit from annealing as a post-processing step.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Annealing a 3D-printed part allows for better internal layer bonding due to recrystallization of the part.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] It allows for an increase in mechanical properties, some of which are fracture toughness, flexural strength, impact resistance, and heat resistance.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Annealing a component may not be suitable for applications where dimensional accuracy is required, as it can introduce warpage or shrinkage due to heating and cooling.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some additively manufactured parts—especially parts that are mission critical—are post-processed with hot isostatic pressing to improve the density and to configure the microstructure to get the required mechanical performance of the printed parts.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Additive or subtractive hybrid manufacturing (ASHM) is a method that involves producing a 3D printed part and using machining (subtractive manufacturing) to remove material.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Machining operations can be completed after each layer, or after the entire 3D print has been completed depending on the application requirements.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] These hybrid methods allow for 3D-printed parts to achieve better surface finishes and dimensional accuracy.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The layered structure of traditional additive manufacturing processes leads to a stair-stepping effect on part-surfaces that are curved or tilted with respect to the building platform.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The effect strongly depends on the layer height used, as well as the orientation of a part surface inside the building process.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This effect can be minimized using "variable layer heights" or "adaptive layer heights".
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] These methods decrease the layer height in places where higher quality is needed.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Painting a 3D-printed part offers a range of finishes and appearances that may not be achievable through most 3D printing techniques.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The process typically involves several steps, such as surface preparation, priming, and painting.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] These steps help prepare the surface of the part and ensuring the paint adheres properly.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques are capable of using multiple materials simultaneously.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] These techniques are able to print in multiple colors and color combinations simultaneously and can produce parts that may not necessarily require painting.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some printing techniques require internal supports to be built to support overhanging features during construction.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] These supports must be mechanically removed or dissolved if using a water-soluble support material such as PVA after completing a print.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some commercial metal 3D printers involve cutting the metal component off the metal substrate after deposition.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A new process for the GMAW 3D printing allows for substrate surface modifications to remove aluminium or steel.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Traditionally, 3D printing focused on polymers for printing, due to the ease of manufacturing and handling polymeric materials.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] However, the method has rapidly evolved to not only print various polymers but also metals, chocolates, and ceramics, making 3D printing a versatile option for manufacturing.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Layer-by-layer fabrication of three-dimensional physical models is a modern concept that "stems from the ever-growing CAD industry, more specifically the solid modeling side of CAD.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Before solid modeling was introduced in the late 1980s, three-dimensional models were created with wire frames and surfaces." but in all cases the layers of materials are controlled by the printer and the material properties.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The three-dimensional material layer is controlled by the deposition rate as set by the printer operator and stored in a computer file.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The earliest printed patented material was a hot melt type ink for printing patterns using a heated metal alloy.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Charles Hull filed the first patent on August 8, 1984, to use a UV-cured acrylic resin using a UV-masked light source at UVP Corp to build a simple model.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 was the first SL product announced by 3D Systems at Autofact Exposition, Detroit, November 1978.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 Beta shipped in Jan 1988 to Baxter Healthcare, Pratt and Whitney, General Motors and AMP.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The first production SLA-1 shipped to Precision Castparts in April 1988.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The UV resin material changed over quickly to an epoxy-based material resin.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In both cases, SLA-1 models needed UV oven curing after being rinsed in a solvent cleaner to remove uncured boundary resin.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A post cure apparatus (PCA) was sold with all systems.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The early resin printers required a blade to move fresh resin over the model on each layer.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The layer thickness was 0.006 inches and the HeCd laser model of the SLA-1 was 12 watts and swept across the surface at 30 inch per second.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] UVP was acquired by 3D Systems in January 1990.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A review of the history shows that a number of materials (resins, plastic powder, plastic filament and hot-melt plastic ink) were used in the 1980s for patents in the rapid prototyping field.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Masked lamp UV-cured resin was also introduced by Cubital's Itzchak Pomerantz in the Soldier 5600, Carl Deckard's (DTM) laser sintered thermoplastic powders, and adhesive-laser cut paper (LOM) stacked to form objects by Michael Feygin before 3D Systems made its first announcement.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The most common polymers for personal 3D printers are polylactic acid (PLA) and PETG.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Efforts to achieve multi-material 3D printing range from enhanced FDM-like processes like VoxelJet to novel voxel-based printing technologies like layered assembly.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A drawback of many existing 3D printing technologies is that they only allow one material to be printed at a time, limiting many potential applications that require the integration of different materials in the same object.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Multi-material 3D printing solves this problem by allowing objects of complex and heterogeneous arrangements of materials to be manufactured using a single printer.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Here, a material must be specified for each voxel (or 3D printing pixel element) inside the final object volume.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The process can be fraught with complications, however, due to the isolated and monolithic algorithms.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some commercial devices have sought to solve these issues, such as building a Spec2Fab translator, but the progress is still very limited.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Nonetheless, in the medical industry, a concept of 3D-printed pills and vaccines has been presented.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] With this new concept, multiple medications can be combined, which is expected to decrease many risks.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] With more and more applications of multi-material 3D printing, the costs of daily life and high technology development will become inevitably lower.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Metallographic materials of 3D printing is also being researched.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] By classifying each material, CIMP-3D can systematically perform 3D printing with multiple materials.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Using 3D printing and multi-material structures in additive manufacturing has allowed for the design and creation of what is called 4D printing.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing is an additive manufacturing process in which the printed object changes shape with time, temperature, or some other type of stimulation.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing allows for the creation of dynamic structures with adjustable shapes, properties or functionality.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The smart/stimulus-responsive materials that are created using 4D printing can be activated to create calculated responses such as self-assembly, self-repair, multi-functionality, reconfiguration and shape-shifting.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This allows for customized printing of shape-changing and shape-memory materials.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing has the potential to find new applications and uses for materials (plastics, composites, metals, etc.) and has the potential to create new alloys and composites that were not viable before.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The versatility of this technology and materials can lead to advances in multiple fields of industry, including space, commercial and medical fields.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The repeatability, precision, and material range for 4D printing must increase to allow the process to become more practical throughout these industries.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] To become a viable industrial production option, there are a few challenges that 4D printing must overcome.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The challenges of 4D printing include the fact that the microstructures of these printed smart materials must be close to or better than the parts obtained through traditional machining processes.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] New and customizable materials need to be developed that have the ability to consistently respond to varying external stimuli and change to their desired shape.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] There is also a need to design new software for the various technique types of 4D printing.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The 4D printing software will need to take into consideration the base smart material, printing technique, and structural and geometric requirements of the design.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A variety of processes, equipment, and materials are used in the production of a three-dimensional object via additive manufacturing.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Techniques include jetting, extrusion, additive friction stir deposition, powder bed fusion, binder jetting, stereolithography, computed axial lithography, liquid alternative, lamination, directed energy deposition, selective powder deposition, and cryogenic manufacturing.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing or additive manufacturing has been used in manufacturing, medical, industry and sociocultural sectors (e.g. cultural heritage) to create successful commercial technology.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] More recently, 3D printing has also been used in the humanitarian and development sector to produce a range of medical items, prosthetics, spares and repairs.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The earliest application of additive manufacturing was on the toolroom end of the manufacturing spectrum.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] For example, rapid prototyping was one of the earliest additive variants, and its mission was to reduce the lead time and cost of developing prototypes of new parts and devices, which was earlier only done with subtractive toolroom methods such as CNC milling, turning, and precision grinding.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, additive manufacturing entered production to a much greater extent.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing of food is being developed by squeezing out food, layer by layer, into three-dimensional objects.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] A large variety of foods are appropriate candidates, such as chocolate and candy, and flat foods such as crackers, pasta, and pizza.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] NASA is looking into the technology in order to create 3D-printed food to limit food waste and to make food that is designed to fit an astronaut's dietary needs.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, Italian bioengineer Giuseppe Scionti developed a technology allowing the production of fibrous plant-based meat analogues using a custom 3D bioprinter, mimicking meat texture and nutritional values.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has entered the world of clothing, with fashion designers experimenting with 3D-printed bikinis, shoes, and dresses.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In commercial production, Nike used 3D printing to prototype and manufacture the 2012 Vapor Laser Talon football shoe for players of American football, and New Balance has 3D manufactured custom-fit shoes for athletes.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has come to the point where companies are printing consumer-grade eyewear with on-demand custom fit and styling (although they cannot print the lenses).
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] On-demand customization of glasses is possible with rapid prototyping.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Armor-design strategies can be enhanced by taking inspiration from nature and prototyping those designs using AM.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In cars, trucks, and aircraft, additive manufacturing is beginning to transform both unibody and fuselage design and production, and powertrain design and production.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] For example, General Electric uses high-end 3D printers to build parts for turbines.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Many of these systems are used for rapid prototyping before mass production methods are employed.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] AM's impact on firearms involves two dimensions: new manufacturing methods for established companies, and new possibilities for the making of do-it-yourself firearms.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2012, the US-based group Defense Distributed disclosed plans to design a working plastic 3D-printed firearm "that could be downloaded and reproduced by anybody with a 3D printer".
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] After Defense Distributed released their plans, questions were raised regarding the effects that 3D printing and widespread consumer-level CNC machining may have on gun control effectiveness.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Surgical uses of 3D printing-centric therapies began in the mid-1990s with anatomical modeling for bony reconstructive surgery planning.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Patient-matched implants were a natural extension of this work, leading to truly personalized implants that fit one unique individual.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Virtual planning of surgery and guidance using 3D printed, personalized instruments have been applied to many areas of surgery including total joint replacement and craniomaxillofacial reconstruction with great success.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] One example of this is the bioresorbable trachial splint to treat newborns with tracheobronchomalacia developed at the University of Michigan.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The use of additive manufacturing for serialized production of orthopedic implants (metals) is also increasing due to the ability to efficiently create porous surface structures that facilitate osseointegration.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The hearing aid and dental industries are expected to be the biggest areas of future development using custom 3D printing technology.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing is not just limited to inorganic materials; there have been a number of biomedical advancements made possible by 3D printing.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] As of 2012, 3D bio-printing technology has been studied by biotechnology firms and academia for possible use in tissue engineering applications in which organs and body parts are built using inkjet printing techniques.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In this process, layers of living cells are deposited onto a gel medium or sugar matrix and slowly built up to form three-dimensional structures including vascular systems.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has been considered as a method of implanting stem cells capable of generating new tissues and organs in living humans.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, 3D printing technology was used for the first time to create a matrix for cell immobilization in fermentation.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Propionic acid production by *Propionibacterium acidipropionici* immobilized on 3D-printed nylon beads was chosen as a model study.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] It was shown that those 3D-printed beads were capable of promoting high-density cell attachment and propionic acid production, which could be adapted to other fermentation bioprocesses.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been employed by researchers in the pharmaceutical field.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] During the last few years, there has been a surge in academic interest regarding drug delivery with the aid of AM techniques.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] This technology offers a unique way for materials to be utilized in novel formulations.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] AM manufacturing allows for the usage of materials and compounds in the development of formulations, in ways that are not possible with conventional/traditional techniques in the pharmaceutical field, e.g. tableting, cast-molding, etc.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Moreover, one of the major advantages of 3D printing, especially in the case of fused deposition modelling (FDM), is the personalization of the dosage form that can be achieved, thus, targeting the patient's specific needs.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In the not-so-distant future, 3D printers are expected to reach hospitals and pharmacies in order to provide on-demand production of personalized formulations according to the patients' needs.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been used for medical equipment.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic 3D printers were used to supplement the strained supply of PPE through volunteers using their personally owned printers to produce various pieces of personal protective equipment (i.e. frames for face shields).
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing, and open source 3D printers, in particular, are the latest technologies making inroads into the classroom.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Higher education has proven to be a major buyer of desktop and professional 3D printers which industry experts generally view as a positive indicator.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Some authors have claimed that 3D printers offer an unprecedented "revolution" in STEM education.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The evidence for such claims comes from both the low-cost ability for rapid prototyping in the classroom by students, but also the fabrication of low-cost high-quality scientific equipment from open hardware designs forming open-source labs.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Additionally, Libraries around the world have also become locations to house smaller 3D printers for educational and community access.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Future applications for 3D printing might include creating open-source scientific equipment.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, 3D printing became intensively used in the cultural heritage field for preservation, restoration and dissemination purposes.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Many Europeans and North American Museums have purchased 3D printers and actively recreate missing pieces of their relics and archaeological monuments such as Tiwanaku in Bolivia.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The Metropolitan Museum of Art and the British Museum have started using their 3D printers to create museum souvenirs that are available in the museum shops.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Other museums, like the National Museum of Military History and Varna Historical Museum, have gone further and sell through the online platform Threeding digital models of their artifacts, created using Artec 3D scanners, in 3D printing friendly file format, which everyone can 3D print at home.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Morehshin Allahyari, an Iranian-born U.S. artist, considers her use of 3D sculpting processes of re-constructing Iranian cultural treasures as feminist activism.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Allahyari uses a 3D modeling software to reconstruct a series of cultural artifacts that were demolished by ISIS militants in 2014.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The application of 3D printing for the representation of architectural assets has many challenges.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, the structure of Iran National Bank was traditionally surveyed and modeled in computer graphics software (specifically, Cinema4D) and was optimized for 3D printing.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The team tested the technique for the construction of the part and it was successful.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] After testing the procedure, the modellers reconstructed the structure in Cinema4D and exported the front part of the model to Netfabb.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The entrance of the building was chosen due to the 3D printing limitations and the budget of the project for producing the maquette.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing was only one of the capabilities enabled by the produced 3D model of the bank, but due to the project's limited scope, the team did not continue modelling for the virtual representation or other applications.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2021, Parsinejad et al. comprehensively compared the hand surveying method for 3D reconstruction ready for 3D printing with digital recording (adoption of photogrammetry method).
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The world's first 3D-printed steel bridge was unveiled in Amsterdam in July 2021.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Spanning 12 meters over the Oudezijds Achterburgwal canal, the bridge was created using robotic arms that printed over 4,500 kilograms of stainless steel.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printed soft actuators is a growing application of 3D printing technology that has found its place in the 3D printing applications.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] These soft actuators are being developed to deal with soft structures and organs, especially in biomedical sectors and where the interaction between humans and robots is inevitable.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The majority of the existing soft actuators are fabricated by conventional methods that require manual fabrication of devices, post-processing/assembly, and lengthy iterations until the maturity of the fabrication is achieved.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Instead of the tedious and time-consuming aspects of the current fabrication processes, researchers are exploring an appropriate manufacturing approach for the effective fabrication of soft actuators.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Thus, 3D-printed soft actuators are introduced to revolutionize the design and fabrication of soft actuators with custom geometrical, functional, and control properties in a faster and inexpensive approach.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] They also enable incorporation of all actuator components into a single structure eliminating the need to use external joints, adhesives, and fasteners.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Circuit board manufacturing involves multiple steps which include imaging, drilling, plating, solder mask coating, nomenclature printing and surface finishes.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] These steps include many chemicals such as harsh solvents and acids.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing circuit boards remove the need for many of these steps while still producing complex designs.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Polymer ink is used to create the layers of the build while silver polymer is used for creating the traces and holes used to allow electricity to flow.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Current circuit board manufacturing can be a tedious process depending on the design.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Specified materials are gathered and sent into inner layer processing where images are printed, developed and etched.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The etch cores are typically punched to add lamination tooling.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The cores are then prepared for lamination.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The stack-up, the buildup of a circuit board, is built and sent into lamination where the layers are bonded.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The boards are then measured and drilled.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Many steps may differ from this stage however for simple designs, the material goes through a plating process to plate the holes and surface.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The outer image is then printed, developed and etched.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] After the image is defined, the material must get coated with a solder mask for later soldering.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Nomenclature is then added so components can be identified later.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The boards are routed out of panel form into their singular or array form and then electrically tested.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Aside from the paperwork that must be completed which proves the boards meet specifications, the boards are then packed and shipped.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The benefits of 3D printing would be that the final outline is defined from the beginning, no imaging, punching or lamination is required and electrical connections are made with the silver polymer which eliminates drilling and plating.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The final paperwork would also be greatly reduced due to the lack of materials required to build the circuit board.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Complex designs which may take weeks to complete through normal processing can be 3D printed, greatly reducing manufacturing time.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2005, academic journals began to report on the possible artistic applications of 3D printing technology.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Off-the-shelf machines were increasingly capable of producing practical household applications, for example, ornamental objects.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Some practical examples include a working clock and gears printed for home woodworking machines among other purposes.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Websites associated with home 3D printing tended to include backscratchers, coat hooks, door knobs, etc.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] As of 2017, domestic 3D printing was reaching a consumer audience beyond hobbyists and enthusiasts.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Several projects and companies are making efforts to develop affordable 3D printers for home desktop use.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Much of this work has been driven by and targeted at DIY/maker/enthusiast/early adopter communities, with additional ties to the academic and hacker communities.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Sped on by decreases in price and increases in quality, As of 2019 an estimated 2 million people worldwide have purchased a 3D printer for hobby use.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has existed for decades within certain manufacturing industries where many legal regimes, including patents, industrial design rights, copyrights, and trademarks may apply.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] However, there is not much jurisprudence to say how these laws will apply if 3D printers become mainstream and individuals or hobbyist communities begin manufacturing items for personal use, for non-profit distribution, or for sale.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Any of the mentioned legal regimes may prohibit the distribution of the designs used in 3D printing or the distribution or sale of the printed item.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] To be allowed to do these things, where active intellectual property was involved, a person would have to contact the owner and ask for a licence, which may come with conditions and a price.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] However, many patent, design and copyright laws contain a standard limitation or exception for "private" or "non-commercial" use of inventions, designs or works of art protected under intellectual property (IP).
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] That standard limitation or exception may leave such private, non-commercial uses outside the scope of IP rights.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Patents cover inventions including processes, machines, manufacturing, and compositions of matter and have a finite duration which varies between countries, but generally 20 years from the date of application.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Therefore, if a type of wheel is patented, printing, using, or selling such a wheel could be an infringement of the patent.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Copyright covers an expression in a tangible, fixed medium and often lasts for the life of the author plus 70 years thereafter.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] For example, a sculptor retains copyright over a statue, such that other people cannot then legally distribute designs to print an identical or similar statue without paying royalties, waiting for the copyright to expire, or working within a fair use exception.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] When a feature has both artistic (copyrightable) and functional (patentable) merits when the question has appeared in US court, the courts have often held the feature is not copyrightable unless it can be separated from the functional aspects of the item.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Attempting to restrict the distribution of gun plans via the Internet has been likened to the futility of preventing the widespread distribution of DeCSS, which enabled DVD ripping.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] After the US government had Defense Distributed take down the plans, they were still widely available via the Pirate Bay and other file sharing sites.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Downloads of the plans from the UK, Germany, Spain, and Brazil were heavy.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Some US legislators have proposed regulations on 3D printers to prevent them from being used for printing guns.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing advocates have suggested that such regulations would be futile, could cripple the 3D printing industry and could infringe on free speech rights, with early pioneers of 3D printing professor Hod Lipson suggesting that gunpowder could be controlled instead.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Internationally, where gun controls are generally stricter than in the United States, some commentators have said the impact may be more strongly felt since alternative firearms are not as easily obtainable.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Officials in the United Kingdom have noted that producing a 3D-printed gun would be illegal under their gun control laws.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Europol stated that criminals have access to other sources of weapons but noted that as technology improves, the risks of an effect would increase.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In the United States, the FAA has anticipated a desire to use additive manufacturing techniques and has been considering how best to regulate this process.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The FAA has jurisdiction over such fabrication because all aircraft parts must be made under FAA production approval or under other FAA regulatory categories.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In December 2016, the FAA approved the production of a 3D-printed fuel nozzle for the GE LEAP engine.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Aviation attorney Jason Dickstein has suggested that additive manufacturing is merely a production method, and should be regulated like any other production method.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] He has suggested that the FAA's focus should be on guidance to explain compliance, rather than on changing the existing rules, and that existing regulations and guidance permit a company "to develop a robust quality system that adequately reflects regulatory needs for quality assurance".
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2021, first standards were issued, e.g.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] ASTM ISO/ASTM52900-21 Additive manufacturing general principles, fundamentals and vocabulary, and the above-mentioned ISO/ASTM52900-15.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2023, the ISO/ASTM 52920:2023 defined the requirements for industrial additive manufacturing processes and production sites using additive manufacturing to ensure required quality level.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Aforetime in Germany there was a draft of DIN norm issued, DIN SPEC 17071:2019.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Polymer feedstock materials can release ultrafine particles and volatile organic compounds (VOCs) if sufficiently heated, which in combination have been associated with adverse respiratory and cardiovascular health effects.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In addition, temperatures of 190 °C to 260 °C are typically reached by an FFF extrusion nozzle, which can cause skin burns.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Vat photopolymerization stereolithography printers use high-powered lasers that present a skin and eye hazard, although they are considered nonhazardous during printing because the laser is enclosed within the printing chamber.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printers also contain many moving parts that include stepper motors, pulleys, threaded rods, carriages, and small fans, which generally do not have enough power to cause serious injuries but can still trap a user's finger, long hair, or loose clothing.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Most desktop FFF 3D printers do not have any added electrical safety features beyond regular internal fuses or external transformers, although the voltages in the exposed parts of 3D printers usually do not exceed 12V to 24V, which is generally considered safe.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Research on the health and safety concerns of 3D printing is new and in development due to the recent proliferation of 3D printing devices.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2017, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work published a discussion paper on the processes and materials involved in 3D printing, the potential implications of this technology for occupational safety and health and avenues for controlling potential hazards.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Noise level is measured in decibels (dB), and can vary greatly in home printers from 15 dB to 75 dB.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Some main sources of noise in filament printers are fans, motors and bearings, while in resin printers the fans usually are responsible for most of the noise.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Some methods for dampening the noise from a printer may be to install vibration isolation, use larger diameter fans, perform regular maintenance and lubrication, or use a soundproofing enclosure.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing, starting with today's infancy period, requires manufacturing firms to be flexible, ever-improving users of all available technologies to remain competitive.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Advocates of additive manufacturing also predict that this arc of technological development will counter globalization, as end users will do much of their own manufacturing rather than engage in trade to buy products from other people and corporations.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The real integration of the newer additive technologies into commercial production, however, is more a matter of complementing traditional subtractive methods rather than displacing them entirely.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The futurologist Jeremy Rifkin claimed that 3D printing signals the beginning of a third industrial revolution, succeeding the production line assembly that dominated manufacturing starting in the late 19th century.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Since the 1950s, a number of writers and social commentators have speculated in some depth about the social and cultural changes that might result from the advent of commercially affordable additive manufacturing technology.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In recent years, 3D printing has created a significant impact in the humanitarian and development sector.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Its potential to facilitate distributed manufacturing is resulting in supply chain and logistics benefits, by reducing the need for transportation, warehousing and wastage.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Furthermore, social and economic development is being advanced through the creation of local production economies.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Others have suggested that as more and more 3D printers start to enter people's homes, the conventional relationship between the home and the workplace might get further eroded.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Likewise, it has also been suggested that, as it becomes easier for businesses to transmit designs for new objects around the globe, so the need for high-speed freight services might also become less.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Finally, given the ease with which certain objects can now be replicated, it remains to be seen whether changes will be made to current copyright legislation so as to protect intellectual property rights with the new technology widely available.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Some call attention to the conjunction of commons-based peer production with 3D printing and other low-cost manufacturing techniques.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The self-reinforced fantasy of a system of eternal growth can be overcome with the development of economies of scope, and here, society can play an important role contributing to the raising of the whole productive structure to a higher plateau of more sustainable and customized productivity.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Further, it is true that many issues, problems, and threats arise due to the democratization of the means of production, and especially regarding the physical ones.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] For instance, the recyclability of advanced nanomaterials is still questioned; weapons manufacturing could become easier; not to mention the implications for counterfeiting and on intellectual property.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] It might be maintained that in contrast to the industrial paradigm whose competitive dynamics were about economies of scale, commons-based peer production 3D printing could develop economies of scope.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] While the advantages of scale rest on cheap global transportation, the economies of scope share infrastructure costs (intangible and tangible productive resources), taking advantage of the capabilities of the fabrication tools.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] And following Neil Gershenfeld in that "some of the least developed parts of the world need some of the most advanced technologies", commons-based peer production and 3D printing may offer the necessary tools for thinking globally but acting locally in response to certain needs.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Larry Summers wrote about the "devastating consequences" of 3D printing and other technologies (robots, artificial intelligence, etc.) for those who perform routine tasks.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In his view, "already there are more American men on disability insurance than doing production work in manufacturing.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Michael Spence wrote that "Now comes a ... powerful, wave of digital technology that is replacing labor in increasingly complex tasks.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] This process of labor substitution and disintermediation has been underway for some time in service sectors—think of ATMs, online banking, enterprise resource planning, customer relationship management, mobile payment systems, and much more.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] This revolution is spreading to the production of goods, where robots and 3D printing are displacing labor." In his view, the vast majority of the cost of digital technologies comes at the start, in the design of hardware (e.g.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printers) and, more importantly, in creating the software that enables machines to carry out various tasks.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] "Once this is achieved, the marginal cost of the hardware is relatively low (and declines as scale rises), and the marginal cost of replicating the software is essentially zero.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Spence believes that, unlike prior digital technologies, which drove firms to deploy underutilized pools of valuable labor around the world, the motivating force in the current wave of digital technologies "is cost reduction via the replacement of labor".
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] For example, as the cost of 3D printing technology declines, it is "easy to imagine" that production may become "extremely" local and customized.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Moreover, production may occur in response to actual demand, not anticipated or forecast demand.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Spence believes that labor, no matter how inexpensive, will become a less important asset for growth and employment expansion, with labor-intensive, process-oriented manufacturing becoming less effective, and that re-localization will appear in both developed and developing countries.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In his view, production will not disappear, but it will be less labor-intensive, and all countries will eventually need to rebuild their growth models around digital technologies and the human capital supporting their deployment and expansion.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Spence writes that "the world we are entering is one in which the most powerful global flows will be ideas and digital capital, not goods, services, and traditional capital.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Naomi Wu regards the usage of 3D printing in the Chinese classroom (where rote memorization is standard) to teach design principles and creativity as the most exciting recent development of the technology, and more generally regards 3D printing as being the next desktop publishing revolution.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] A printer was donated to the Juan Fernandez Women's Group in 2024, to support women in the remote community to be able to create parts to fix broken equipment, without having to wait for a ship to import the needed components.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The growth of additive manufacturing could have a large impact on the environment.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Traditional subtractive manufacturing methods such as CNC milling create products by cutting away material from a larger block.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In contrast, additive manufacturing creates products layer-by layer, using the minimum required materials to create the product.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] This has the benefit of reducing material waste, which further contributes to energy savings by avoiding raw material production.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Life-cycle assessment of additive manufacturing has estimated that adopting the technology could further lower carbon dioxide emissions since 3D printing creates localized production, thus reducing the need to transport products and the emissions associated.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] AM could also allow consumers to create their own replacement parts to fix purchased products to extend the lifespan of purchased products.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] By making only the bare structural necessities of products, additive manufacturing also has the potential to make profound contributions to lightweighting.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The use of these lightweight components would allow for reductions in the energy consumption and greenhouse gas emissions of vehicles and other forms of transportation.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] A case study on an airplane component made using additive manufacturing, for example, found that the use of the component saves 63% of relevant energy and carbon dioxide emissions over the course of the product's lifetime.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] However, the adoption of additive manufacturing also has environmental disadvantages.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Firstly, AM has a high energy consumption compared to traditional processes.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] This is due to its use of processes such as lasers and high temperatures for product creation.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Secondly, despite additive manufacturing reducing up to 90% of waste compared to subtractive manufacturing, AM can generate waste that is non-recyclable.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] For example, there are issues with the recyclability of materials in metal AM as some highly regulated industries such as aerospace often insist on using virgin powder in the creation of safety critical components.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing has not yet reached its theoretical material efficiency potential of 97%, but it may get closer as the technology continues to increase productivity.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Despite the drawbacks, research and industry are making further strides to support AM's sustainability.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Some large FDM printers that melt high-density polyethylene (HDPE) pellets may also accept sufficiently clean recycled material such as chipped milk bottles.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In addition, these printers can use shredded material from faulty builds or unsuccessful prototype versions, thus reducing overall project wastage and materials handling and storage.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The concept has been explored in the RecycleBot.
[src:manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] There are also industrial efforts to produce metal powder from recycled metals.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Other common names for abalone are ear shells, sea ears, and, now rarely, muttonfish or muttonshells in parts of Australia, ormer in the United Kingdom, perlemoen in South Africa, and pāua in New Zealand.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Most abalone vary in size from 20 mm (0.8 in) (*Haliotis pulcherrima*) to 200 mm (8 in).
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The largest species, *Haliotis rufescens*, reaches 300 mm (12 in).
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The shells of abalone have a low, open spiral structure, and are characterized by several open respiratory pores in a row near the shell's outer edge.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The thick inner layer of the shell is composed of nacre, which in many species is highly iridescent, giving rise to a range of strong, changeable colors which make the shells attractive to humans as ornaments, jewelry, and as a source of colorful mother-of-pearl.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The shell of abalone is convex, rounded to oval in shape, and may be highly arched or very flattened.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The shell of the majority of species has a small, flat spire and two to three whorls.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The last whorl, known as the body whorl, is auriform, meaning that the shell resembles an ear, giving rise to the common name "ear shell".
[src:manufacturing/abalone] *Haliotis asinina* has a somewhat different shape, as it is more elongated and distended.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The shell of *Haliotis cracherodii cracherodii* is also unusual as it has an ovate form, is imperforate, shows an exserted spire, and has prickly ribs.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] A mantle cleft in the shell impresses a groove in the shell, in which are the row of holes characteristic of the genus.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] These holes are respiratory apertures for venting water from the gills and for releasing sperm and eggs into the water column.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] They make up what is known as the selenizone, which forms as the shell grows.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] This series of eight to 38 holes is near the anterior margin.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The older holes are gradually sealed up as the shell grows and new holes form.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Each species has a typical number of open holes, between four and 10, in the selenizone.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The aperture of the shell is very wide and nacreous.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The exterior of the shell is striated and dull.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The color of the shell is very variable from species to species, which may reflect the animal's diet.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The iridescent nacre that lines the inside of the shell varies in color from silvery white, to pink, red and green-red to deep blue, green to purple.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The animal has fimbriated head lobes and side lobes that are fimbriated and cirrated.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The radula has small median teeth, and the lateral teeth are single and beam-like.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] They have about 70 uncini, with denticulated hooks, the first four very large.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The rounded foot is very large in comparison to most molluscs.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The soft body is coiled around the columellar muscle, and its insertion, instead of being on the columella, is on the middle of the inner wall of the shell.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The gills are symmetrical and both well developed.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] These snails cling solidly with their broad, muscular foot to rocky surfaces at sublittoral depths, although some species such as *Haliotis cracherodii* used to be common in the intertidal zone.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone reach maturity at a relatively small size.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Their fecundity is high and increases with their size, laying from 10,000 to 11 million eggs at a time.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The spermatozoa are filiform and pointed at one end, and the anterior end is a rounded head.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The adults are herbivorous and feed with their rhipidoglossan radula on macroalgae, preferring red or brown algae.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Sizes vary from 20 mm (25⁄32 in) (*Haliotis pulcherrima*) to 200 mm (7+7⁄8 in), while *Haliotis rufescens* is the largest of the genus at 30 cm (12 in).
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The haliotid family has a worldwide distribution, along the coastal waters of every continent, except the Pacific coast of South America, the Atlantic coast of North America, the Arctic, and Antarctica.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The majority of abalone species are found in cold waters, such as off the coasts of New Zealand, South Africa, Australia, Western North America, and Japan.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone are members of the clade Vetigastropoda, though their precise position within the clade is uncertain.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Despite their inclusion in the order Lepetellida, they do not appear to be particularly closely related to other members of the order and may be more closely related to Trochoidea, or alternatively outside of a clade uniting Trochoidea with the rest of Lepetellida.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The earliest known fossil abalone are known from the Campanian age of the Late Cretaceous.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The few known Cretaceous abalone fossils have all been found in North America, suggesting that the group may have originated there, although other possibilities have been suggested, including a central Indo-Pacific origin based on where abalone are most diverse today.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Haliotidae may have evolved from the pleurotomariidan families Temnotropidae or Trochotomidae.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] *Trochotoma frydai*, from the Campanian of Spain, closely resembles the Cretaceous abalone *Haliotis antillesensis* except in having a slit instead of a row of tremata.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The shell of the abalone is exceptionally strong and is composed of a tightly packed calcium carbonate matrix.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Layered among the matrix is an endogenous protein further strengthening the shell.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Due to the unique structure of the shell, a force applied directly to the shell matrix will more likely cause the shedding of layers as opposed to cracking or shattering.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Material scientists are currently studying this structure for insight into stronger ablative protective tools such as body armor.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The dust created by grinding and cutting abalone shell is dangerous; appropriate safeguards must be taken to protect people from inhaling these particles.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone are subject to various infectious diseases.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The Victorian Department of Primary Industries said in 2007 that ganglioneuritis killed up to 90% of stock in affected regions.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone possess very little clotting factor, meaning even a mild to moderate skin-piercing injury can result in death from fluid loss.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Members of the Spionidae of the polychaetes are known as pests of abalone.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone have been harvested for seafood and aesthetics since prehistory.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone shells and associated materials, like their claw-like pearls and nacre, have been used as jewelry and for buttons, buckles and inlay.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] These shells have been found in archaeological sites around the world, ranging from 100,000-year-old deposits at Blombos Cave in South Africa to historic Chinese abalone middens on California's Northern Channel Islands.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] For at least 12,000 years, abalone were harvested to such an extent around the Channel Islands that shells in the area decreased in size four thousand years ago.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Aquafarming of abalone as a meat product began in the late 1950s and early 1960s in Japan and China.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Since the mid-1990s, there have been many increasingly successful endeavors to commercially farm abalone for the purpose of consumption.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Overfishing and poaching have reduced wild populations to such an extent that farmed abalone now supplies most of the abalone meat consumed.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The principal abalone farming regions are Mainland China, Taiwan, Japan and South Korea.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone is also farmed in Australia, Canada, Chile, France, Iceland, Ireland, Mexico, Namibia, New Zealand, South Africa, Spain, Thailand and the United States.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] After trials in 2012, a commercial "sea ranch" was set up in Flinders Bay, Western Australia, to raise abalone.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The ranch is based on an artificial reef made up of 5,000 separate concrete abalone habitat units, which can host 400 abalone each.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The reef is seeded with young abalone from an onshore hatchery.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The abalone feed on seaweed that grows naturally on the habitats; the ecosystem enrichment of the bay also results in growing numbers of dhufish, pink snapper, wrasse, and Samson fish among other species.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone have long been a valuable food source for humans in every area of the world where a species is abundant.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The meat of this mollusc is considered a delicacy in certain parts of Latin America (particularly Chile), France, New Zealand, East Asia and Southeast Asia.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In the Greater China region and among overseas Chinese communities, abalone is commonly known as *bao yu*, and sometimes forms part of a Chinese banquet as one of the four sea delicacies of Chinese cuisine.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In the same way as shark fin soup or bird's nest soup, abalone is considered a luxury item, and is traditionally reserved for celebrations.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In Japan, live and raw abalone are used in sushi (known as *awabi*) or served steamed, salted, boiled, chopped, or simmered in soy sauce.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Salted, fermented abalone entrails are the main component of *tottsuru*, a local dish from Honshū.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In South Korea, abalone is called *Jeonbok* and used in various recipes.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] *Jeonbok* porridge and pan-fried abalone steak with butter are popular, but it's also commonly used in soups or ramyeon.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In California, US, abalone meat can be found on pizza, sautéed with caramelized mango, or in steak form dusted with cracker meal and flour.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] As abalone became more popular and less common, the prices adjusted accordingly.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In the 1920s, a restaurant-served portion of abalone, about 4 ounces (110 g), would cost (in inflation adjusted dollars) about US$7; by 2004, the price had risen to US$75.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In the United States, prior to this time, abalone was predominantly eaten, gathered, and prepared by Chinese immigrants.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Before that, abalone were collected to be eaten, and used for other purposes by Native American tribes.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] By 1900, laws were passed in California to outlaw the taking of abalone above the intertidal zone.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] This forced the Chinese out of the market and the Japanese perfected diving, with or without gear, to enter the market.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone started to become popular in the US after the Panama–Pacific International Exposition in 1915, which exhibited 365 varieties of fish with cooking demonstrations, and a 1,300-seat dining hall.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Tasmania supplies about 25% of the yearly world abalone harvest.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Around 12,500 Tasmanians recreationally fish for blacklip and greenlip abalone.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] For blacklip abalone, the size limit varies between 138 mm (5.4 in) for the southern end of the state and 127 mm (5.0 in) for the northern end of the state.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Greenlip abalone have a minimum size of 145 mm (5.7 in), except for an area around Perkins Bay in the north of the state where the minimum size is 132 millimetres (5.2 in).
[src:manufacturing/abalone] With a recreational abalone licence, the bag limit is 10 per day, with a total possession limit of 20.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Scuba diving for abalone is allowed, and has a rich history in Australia.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] (Scuba diving for abalone in the states of New South Wales and Western Australia is illegal; a free-diving catch limit of two is allowed).
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Victoria has had an active abalone fishery since the late 1950s.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The state is sectioned into three fishing zones, Eastern, Central and Western, with each fisher required a zone-allocated licence.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Harvesting is performed by divers using surface-supplied air "hookah" systems operating from runabout-style, outboard-powered boats.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] While the diver seeks out colonies of abalone amongst the reef beds, the deckhand operates the boat, known as working "live" and stays above where the diver is working.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Bags of abalone pried from the rocks are brought to the surface by the diver or by way of "shot line", where the deckhand drops a weighted rope for the catch bag to be connected then retrieved.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Divers measure each abalone before removing from the reef and the deckhand remeasures each abalone and removes excess weed growth from the shell.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Since 2002, the Victorian industry has seen a significant decline in catches, with the total allowable catch reduced from 1440 to 787 tonnes for the 2011/12 fishing year, due to dwindling stocks and most notably the abalone virus ganglioneuritis, which is fast-spreading and lethal to abalone stocks.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Sport harvesting of red abalone is permitted with a California fishing license and an abalone stamp card.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In 2008, the abalone card also came with a set of 24 tags.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] This was reduced to 18 abalone per year in 2014, and as of 2017 the limit has been reduced to 12, only nine of which may be taken south of Mendocino County.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Legal-size abalone must be tagged immediately.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone may only be taken using breath-hold techniques or shorepicking; scuba diving for abalone is strictly prohibited.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Taking of abalone is not permitted south of the mouth of San Francisco Bay.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] A size minimum of 7 in (180 mm) measured across the shell is in place.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] A person may be in possession of only three abalone at any given time.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] As of 2017, abalone season is May to October, excluding July.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Transportation of abalone may only legally occur while the abalone is still attached in the shell.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Sale of sport-obtained abalone is illegal, including the shell.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Only red abalone may be taken, as black, white, pink, flat, green, and pinto abalone are protected by law.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In 2018, the California Fish and Game Commission closed recreational abalone season due to dramatically declining populations.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] That year, they extended the moratorium to last through April 2021.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Afterwards, they extended the ban for another 5 years until April 2026.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In December 2025 California extended the ban another 10 years until April 2036.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] An abalone diver is normally equipped with a thick wetsuit, including a hood, bootees, and gloves, and usually also a mask, snorkel, weight belt, abalone iron, and abalone gauge.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Alternatively, the rock picker can feel underneath rocks at low tides for abalone.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone are mostly taken in depths from a few inches up to 10 m (33 ft); less common are freedivers who can work deeper than 10 m (33 ft).
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone are normally found on rocks near food sources such as kelp.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] An abalone iron is used to pry the abalone from the rock before it has time to fully clamp down.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Divers dive from boats, kayaks, tube floats, or directly off the shore.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The largest abalone recorded in California is 12.34 in (31.3 cm), caught by John Pepper somewhere off the coast of San Mateo County in September 1993.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The mollusc *Concholepas concholepas* is often sold in the United States under the name "Chilean abalone", though it is not an abalone, but a muricid.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In New Zealand, abalone is called *pāua* (/ˈpaʊə/, from the Māori language).
[src:manufacturing/abalone] *Haliotis iris* (or blackfoot pāua) is the ubiquitous New Zealand pāua, the highly polished nacre of which is extremely popular as souvenirs with its striking blue, green, and purple iridescence.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] *Haliotis australis* and *Haliotis virginea* are also found in New Zealand waters, but are less popular than *H. iris*.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] *Haliotis pirimoana* is a small species endemic to Manawatāwhi / the Three Kings Islands that superficially resembles *H. virginea*.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Like all New Zealand shellfish, recreational harvesting of *pāua* does not require a permit provided catch limits, size restrictions, and seasonal and local restrictions set by the Ministry for Primary Industries (MPI) are followed.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The legal recreational daily limit is 10 per diver, with a minimum shell length of 125 mm (4.9 in) for *H. iris* and 80 mm (3.1 in) for *H. australis*.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In addition, no person may be in possession, even on land, of more than 20 pāua or more than 2.5 kg (5.5 lb) of pāua meat at any one time.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Pāua can only be caught by free-diving; it is illegal to catch them using scuba gear.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] An extensive global black market exists in collecting and exporting abalone meat.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] This can be a particularly awkward problem where the right to harvest pāua can be granted legally under Māori customary rights.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] When such permits to harvest are abused, it is frequently difficult to police.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The limit is strictly enforced by roving Ministry for Primary Industries fishery officers with the backing of the New Zealand Police.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Poaching is a major industry in New Zealand with many thousands being taken illegally, often undersized.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Convictions have resulted in seizure of diving gear, boats, and motor vehicles and fines and in rare cases, imprisonment.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] There are five species endemic to South Africa, namely *H. parva*, *H. spadicea*, *H. queketti* and *H. speciosa*.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The largest abalone in South Africa, *Haliotis midae*, occurs along roughly two-thirds of the country's coastline.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone-diving has been a recreational activity for many years, but stocks are currently being threatened by illegal commercial harvesting.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In South Africa, all persons harvesting this shellfish need permits that are issued annually, and no abalone may be harvested using scuba gear.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] For the last few years, however, no permits have been issued for collecting abalone, but commercial harvesting still continues as does illegal collection by syndicates.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In 2007, because of widespread poaching of abalone, the South African government listed abalone as an endangered species according to the CITES section III appendix, which requests member governments to monitor the trade in this species.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] This listing was removed from CITES in June 2010 by the South African government and South African abalone is no longer subject to CITES trade controls.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Export permits are still required, however.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The abalone meat from South Africa is prohibited for sale in the country to help reduce poaching; however, much of the illegally harvested meat is sold in Asian countries.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] As of early 2008, the wholesale price for abalone meat was approximately US$40.00 per kilogram.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] There is an active trade in the shells, which sell for more than US$1,400 per tonne.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Ormers (*Haliotis tuberculata*) are considered a delicacy in the British Channel Islands as well as in adjacent areas of France, and are pursued with great alacrity by the locals.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] This, and a recent lethal bacterial disease, has led to a dramatic depletion in numbers since the latter half of the 19th century, and "ormering" is now strictly regulated to preserve stocks.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The gathering of ormers is now restricted to a number of 'ormering tides', from 1 January to 30 April, which occur on the full or new moon and two days following.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] No ormers may be taken from the beach that are under 80 millimetres (3.1 in) in shell length.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Gatherers are not allowed to wear wetsuits or even put their heads underwater.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Any breach of these laws is a criminal offence and can lead to a fine of up to £5,000 or six months in prison.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The demand for ormers is such that they led to the world's first underwater arrest, when Mr.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Kempthorne-Leigh of Guernsey was arrested by a police officer in full diving gear when illegally diving for ormers.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The highly iridescent inner nacre layer of the shell of abalone has traditionally been used as a decorative item, in jewelry, buttons, and as inlay in furniture and musical instruments, such as on fret boards and binding of guitars.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] See article Najeonchilgi regarding Korean handicraft.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone has been an important staple in a number of Indigenous cultures around the world, specifically in Africa and on the Northwest American coast.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The meat is a traditional food, and the shell is used to make ornaments; historically, the shells were also used as currency in some communities.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Abalone are critically threatened due to overfishing and the acidification of oceans as lower pH erodes the calcium carbonate in their shells.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] In the 21st century, white, pink, and green abalone are on the United States federal endangered species list.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Possible restoration sites have been proposed for the San Clemente Island and Santa Barbara Island areas.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Reintroduction of farming abalone to the wild has been proposed, with these abalone having special tags to help track the population.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The number of species that are recognized within the genus *Haliotis* has fluctuated over time, and depends on the source that is consulted.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The number of recognized species range from 30 to 130.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] As of 2025, 76 extant species and 25 fossil species were listed as accepted in MolluscaBase.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] This list finds a compromise using the WoRMS database, plus some species that have been added, for a total of 57.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] The majority of abalone have not been rated for conservation status.
[src:manufacturing/abalone] Those that have been reviewed tend to show that the abalone in general is an animal that is declining in numbers, and will need protection throughout the globe.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] An **abrasive** is a material, often a mineral, that is used to shape or finish a workpiece through rubbing which leads to part of the workpiece being worn away by friction.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] While finishing a material often means polishing it to gain a smooth, reflective surface, the process can also involve roughening as in satin, matte or beaded finishes.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] In short, the ceramics which are used to cut, grind and polish other softer materials are known as abrasives.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Abrasives are extremely commonplace and are used very extensively in a wide variety of industrial, domestic, and technological applications.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] This gives rise to a large variation in the physical and chemical composition of abrasives as well as the shape of the abrasive.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Some common uses for abrasives include grinding, polishing, buffing, honing, cutting, drilling, sharpening, lapping, and sanding (see abrasive machining).
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Files are not abrasives; they remove material not by scratching or rubbing, but by the cutting action of sharp teeth which have been cut into the surface of the file, very much like those of a saw.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] However, diamond files are a form of coated abrasive (as they are metal rods coated with diamond powder).
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Abrasives generally rely upon a difference in hardness between the abrasive and the material being worked upon, the abrasive being the harder of the two substances.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] However, it is not strictly necessary, as any two solid materials that repeatedly rub against each other will tend to wear each other away; examples include, softer shoe soles wearing away wooden or stone steps over decades or centuries or glaciers abrading stone valleys.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] However, even softer minerals like calcium carbonate are used as abrasives, such as "polishing agents" in toothpaste.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] These minerals are either crushed or are already of a sufficiently small size (anywhere from macroscopic grains as large as about 2 mm to microscopic grains about 0.001 mm in diameter) to permit their use as an abrasive.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] These grains, commonly called grit, have rough edges, often terminating in points which will decrease the surface area in contact and increase the localised contact pressure.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] The abrasive and the material to be worked are brought into contact while in relative motion to each other.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Force applied through the grains causes fragments of the worked material to break away, while simultaneously smoothing the abrasive grain and/or causing the grain to work loose from the rest of the abrasive.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Abrasives may be classified as either natural or synthetic.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] When discussing sharpening stones, natural stones have long been considered superior but advances in material technology are seeing this distinction become less distinct.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Many synthetic abrasives are effectively identical to a natural mineral, differing only in that the synthetic mineral has been manufactured rather than mined.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Impurities in the natural mineral may make it less effective.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Some abrasive minerals (such as zirconia alumina) occur naturally but are sufficiently rare or sufficiently more difficult or costly to obtain such that a synthetic stone is used industrially.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Abrasives are shaped for various purposes.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Natural abrasives are often sold as dressed stones, usually in the form of a rectangular block.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Both natural and synthetic abrasives are commonly available in a wide variety of shapes, often coming as bonded or coated abrasives, including blocks, belts, discs, wheels, sheets, rods and loose grains.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] A **bonded abrasive** is composed of an abrasive material contained within a matrix, although very fine aluminium oxide abrasive may comprise sintered material.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] This matrix is called a binder and is often a clay, a resin, a glass or a rubber.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] This mixture of binder and abrasive is typically shaped into blocks, sticks, or wheels.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] The most common abrasive used is aluminium oxide.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Also common are silicon carbide, tungsten carbide and garnet.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Artificial sharpening stones are often a bonded abrasive and are readily available as a two sided block, each side being a different grade of grit.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Grinding wheels are cylinders that are rotated at high speed.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] While once worked with a foot pedal or hand crank, the introduction of electric motors has made it necessary to construct the wheel to withstand greater radial stress to prevent the wheel flying apart as it spins.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Similar issues arise with cutting wheels, which are often structurally reinforced with impregnated fibres.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] High relative speed between abrasive and workpiece often makes necessary the use of a lubricant of some kind.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Traditionally, they were called coolants as they were used to prevent frictional heat build up which could damage the workpiece (such as ruining the temper of a blade).
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Some research suggests that the heat transport property of a lubricant is less important when dealing with metals as the metal will quickly conduct heat from the work surface.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] More important are their effects upon lessening tensile stresses while increasing some compressive stresses and reducing "thermal and mechanical stresses during chip formation".
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Various shapes are also used as heads on rotary tools used in precision work, such as scale modelling.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Bonded abrasives need to be trued and dressed after they are used.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Dressing is the cleaning of the waste material (swarf and loose abrasive) from the surface and exposing fresh grit.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Depending upon the abrasive and how it was used, dressing may involve the abrasive being simply placed under running water and brushed with a stiff brush for a soft stone or the abrasive being ground against another abrasive, such as aluminium oxide used to dress a grinding wheel.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Truing is restoring the abrasive to its original surface shape.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Wheels and stones tend to wear unevenly, leaving the cutting surface no longer flat (said to be "dished out" if it is meant to be a flat stone) or no longer the same diameter across the cutting face.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] This will lead to uneven abrasion and other difficulties.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] A *coated abrasive* comprises an abrasive fixed to a backing material such as paper, cloth, rubber, resin, polyester or even metal, many of which are flexible.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Sandpaper is a very common coated abrasive.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Coated abrasives are most commonly the same minerals as are used for bonded abrasives.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] A bonding agent (often some sort of adhesive or resin) is applied to the backing to provide a flat surface to which the grit is then subsequently adhered.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] A woven backing may also use a filler agent (again, often a resin) to provide additional resilience.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Coated abrasives may be shaped for use in rotary and orbital sanders, for wrapping around sanding blocks, as handpads, as closed loops for use on belt grinders, as striking surfaces on matchboxes, on diamond plates and diamond steels.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Diamond tools, though for cutting, are often abrasive in nature.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Sand, glass beads, metal pellets copper slag and dry ice may all be used for a process called sandblasting (or similar, such as the use of glass beads which is "bead blasting").
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Dry ice will sublimate leaving behind no residual abrasive.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Cutting compound used on automotive paint is an example of an abrasive suspended in a liquid, paste or wax, as are some polishing liquids for silverware and optical media.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] The liquid, paste or wax acts as a binding agent that keeps the abrasive attached to the cloth which is used as a backing to move the abrasive across the work piece.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] On cars in particular, wax may serve as both a protective agent by preventing exposure of the paint of metal to air and also act as an optical filler to make scratches less noticeable.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Toothpaste contains calcium carbonate or silica as a "polishing agent" to remove plaque and other matter from teeth as the hardness of calcium carbonate is less than that of tooth enamel but more than that of the contaminating agent.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Very fine rouge powder was commonly used for grinding glass, being somewhat replaced by modern ceramics, and is still used in jewellery making for a highly reflective finish.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Cleaning products may also contain abrasives suspended in a paste or cream.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] They are chosen to be reasonably safe on some linoleum, tile, metal or stone surfaces.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] However, many laminate surfaces and ceramic topped stoves are easily damaged by these abrasive compounds.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Even ceramic/pottery tableware or cookware can damage these surfaces, particularly the bottom of the tableware, which is often unglazed in part or in whole and acts as simply another bonded abrasive.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Metal pots and stoves are often scoured with abrasive cleaners, typically in the form of the aforementioned cream or paste or of steel wool and non woven scouring pads which holds fine grits abrasives.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Human skin is also subjected to abrasion in the form of exfoliation.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Abrasives for this can be much softer and more exotic than for other purposes and may include things like almond and oatmeal.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Dermabrasion and microdermabrasion are now rather commonplace cosmetic procedures which use mineral abrasives.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Scratched compact discs and DVDs may sometimes be repaired through buffing with a very fine compound, the principle being that a multitude of small scratches will be more optically transparent than a single large scratch.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] However, this does take some skill and will eventually cause the protective coating of the disc to be entirely eroded (especially if the original scratch is deep), at which time, the data surface will be destroyed if abrasion continues.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Silicon carbide powders are commonly used as abrasive materials in various machining processes, including grinding, water-jet cutting, and sandblasting.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] These powders are effective for fine grinding or rough polishing of semiconductors, ceramics, and ferrous materials.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] The shape, size and nature of the workpiece and the desired finish will influence the choice of the abrasive used.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Also, different shapes of adhesive may make it harder to abrade certain areas of the workpiece.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Health hazards can arise from any dust produced (which may be ameliorated through the use of a lubricant) which could lead to silicosis (when the abrasive or workpiece is a silicate) and the choice of any lubricant.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Besides water, oils are the most common lubricants.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] These may present inhalation hazards, contact hazards and, as friction necessarily produces heat, flammable material hazards.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] An abrasive which is too hard or too coarse can remove too much material or leave undesired scratch marks.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Besides being unsightly, scratching can have other, more serious effects.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] A finer or softer abrasive will tend to leave much finer scratch marks which may even be invisible to the naked eye (a "grainless finish"); a softer abrasive may not even significantly abrade a certain object.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] A softer or finer abrasive will take longer to cut, as it tends to cut less deeply than a coarser, harder material.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Also, the softer abrasive may become less effective more quickly as the abrasive is itself abraded.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] This allows fine abrasives to be used in the polishing of metal and lenses where the series of increasingly fine scratches tends to take on a much more shiny or reflective appearance or greater transparency.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Very fine abrasives may be used to coat the strop for a cut-throat razors, however, the purpose of stropping is not to abrade material but to straighten the burr on an edge.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] The final stage of sharpening Japanese swords is called polishing and may be a form of superfinishing.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Different chemical or structural modifications may be made to alter the cutting properties of the abrasive.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Other very important considerations are price and availability.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Diamond, for a long time considered the hardest substance in existence, is actually softer than fullerite and even harder aggregated diamond nanorods, both of which have been synthesised in laboratories, but no commercial process has yet been developed.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Diamond itself is expensive due to scarcity in nature and the cost of synthesising it.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Bauxite is a very common ore which, along with corundum's reasonably high hardness, contributes to corundum's status as a common, inexpensive abrasive.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Thought must be given to the desired task about using an appropriately hard abrasive.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] At one end, using an excessively hard abrasive wastes money by wearing it down when a cheaper, less hard abrasive would suffice.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] At the other end, if the abrasive substance is too soft, abrasion does not take place in a timely fashion, effectively wasting the abrasive as well as any accruing costs associated with loss of time.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Aside from the aforementioned uses of shaping and finishing, abrasives may also be used to prepare surfaces for application of some sort of paint of adhesive.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] An excessively smooth surface may prevent paint and adhesives from adhering as strongly as an irregular surface could allow.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Inflatable tyre repair kits (which, on bicycles particularly, are actually patches for the inner tube rather than the tyre) require use of an abrasive so that the self-vulcanising cement will stick strongly.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Inadvertently, people who use knives on glass or metal cutting boards are abrading their knife blades.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] The pressure at the knife edge can easily create microscopic (or even macroscopic) cuts in the board.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] This cut is a ready source of abrasive material as well as a channel full of this abrasive through which the edge slides.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] For this reason, and without regard for the health benefits, wooden boards are much more desirable.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] A similar occurrence arises with glass-cutters.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Glass-cutters have circular blades that are designed to roll not slide.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] They should never retrace an already effected cut.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] Undesired abrasion may result from the presence of carbon in internal combustion engines.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] While smaller particles are readily transported by the lubrication system, larger carbon particles may abrade components with close tolerances.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] The carbon arises from the excessive heating of engine oil or from incomplete combustion.
[src:manufacturing/abrasive] This soot may contain fullerenes which are noted for their extreme hardness—and small size and limited quantity which would tend to limit their effect.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] An **AC motor** is an electric motor driven by an alternating current (AC).
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The AC motor commonly consists of two basic parts, an outside stator having coils supplied with alternating current to produce a rotating magnetic field, and an inside rotor attached to the output shaft producing a second rotating magnetic field.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The rotor magnetic field may be produced by permanent magnets, reluctance saliency, or DC or AC electrical windings.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Less common, AC linear motors operate on similar principles as rotating motors but have their stationary and moving parts arranged in a straight line configuration, producing linear motion instead of rotation.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The two main types of AC motors are induction motors and synchronous motors.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The induction motor (or asynchronous motor) always relies on a small difference in speed between the stator rotating magnetic field and the rotor shaft speed called slip to induce rotor current in the rotor AC winding.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] As a result, the induction motor cannot produce torque near synchronous speed where induction (or slip) is irrelevant or ceases to exist.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In contrast, the synchronous motor does not rely on slip-induction for operation and uses either permanent magnets, salient poles (having projecting magnetic poles), or an independently excited rotor winding.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The synchronous motor produces its rated torque at exactly synchronous speed.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The brushless wound-rotor doubly fed synchronous motor system has an independently excited rotor winding that does not rely on the principles of slip-induction of current.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The brushless wound-rotor doubly fed motor is a synchronous motor that can function exactly at the supply frequency or sub to super multiple of the supply frequency.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Other types of motors include eddy current motors, and AC and DC mechanically commutated machines in which speed is dependent on voltage and winding connection.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Alternating current technology was rooted in Michael Faraday's and Joseph Henry's 1830–31 discovery that a changing magnetic field can induce an electric current in a circuit.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Faraday is usually given credit for this discovery since he published his findings first.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In 1832, French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii generated a crude form of alternating current when he designed and built the first alternator.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] It consisted of a revolving horseshoe magnet passing over two wound-wire coils.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Because of AC's advantages in long-distance high voltage transmission, there were many inventors in the United States and Europe during the late 19th century trying to develop workable AC motors.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The first person to conceive of a rotating magnetic field was Walter Baily, who gave a workable demonstration of his battery-operated polyphase motor aided by a commutator on 28 June 1879, to the Physical Society of London.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Describing an apparatus nearly identical to Baily's, French electrical engineer Marcel Deprez published a paper in 1880 that identified the rotating magnetic field principle and that of a two-phase AC system of currents to produce it.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Never practically demonstrated, the design was flawed, as one of the two currents was “furnished by the machine itself.” In 1886, English-born American engineer Elihu Thomson built an AC motor by expanding upon the induction-repulsion principle and his wattmeter.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In 1887, American inventor Charles Schenk Bradley was the first to patent a two-phase AC power transmission with four wires.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] "Commutatorless" alternating current induction motors seem to have been independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In 1888, Ferraris published his research to the Royal Academy of Sciences in Turin, where he detailed the foundations of motor operation; Tesla, in the same year, was granted a United States patent for his own motor.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Working from Ferraris's experiments, Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky introduced the first three-phase induction motor in 1890, a much more capable design that became the prototype used in Europe and the U.S.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] He also invented the first three-phase generator and transformer and combined them into the first complete AC three-phase system in 1891.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The three-phase motor design was also worked on by the Swiss engineer Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown, and other three-phase AC systems were developed by German technician Friedrich August Haselwander and Swedish engineer Jonas Wenström.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] If the rotor of a squirrel cage motor were to run at the true synchronous speed, the flux in the rotor at any given place on the rotor would not change, and no current would be created in the squirrel cage.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] For this reason, ordinary squirrel-cage motors run at some tens of revolutions per minute (RPM) slower than synchronous speed.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Because the rotating field (or equivalent pulsating field) effectively rotates faster than the rotor, it could be said to *slip* past the surface of the rotor.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The difference between synchronous speed and actual speed is called **slip**, and loading the motor increases the amount of slip as the motor slows down slightly.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Even with no load, internal mechanical losses prevent the slip from being zero.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The constant 120 results from combining the conversions of 60 seconds per minute and that each phase requires 2 poles.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Actual RPM for an induction motor will be less than this calculated synchronous speed by an amount known as *slip*, that increases with the torque produced.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] With no load, the speed will be very close to synchronous.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] When loaded, standard motors have between 2–3% slip, special motors may have up to 7% slip, and a class of motors known as *torque motors* are rated to operate at 100% slip (i.e., 0 rpm, full stall).
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] As an example, a typical four-pole motor running on 60 Hz might have a nameplate rating of 1725 rpm at full load, while its calculated speed is 1800 rpm.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The speed in this type of motor has traditionally been altered by having additional sets of coils or poles in the motor that can be switched on and off to change the speed of magnetic field rotation.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] However, developments in power electronics mean that the frequency of the power supply can also now be varied to provide a smoother control of the motor speed.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This kind of rotor is the basic hardware for induction regulators, which is an exception of the use of rotating magnetic field as pure electrical (not electromechanical) application.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Most common AC motors use the squirrel-cage rotor, which will be found in virtually all domestic and light industrial alternating current motors.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The squirrel-cage refers to the rotating exercise cage for pet animals.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The motor takes its name from the shape of its rotor "windings"- a ring at either end of the rotor, with bars connecting the rings running the length of the rotor.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] It is typically cast aluminum or copper poured between the iron laminates of the rotor, and usually only the end rings will be visible.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The vast majority of the rotor currents will flow through the bars rather than the higher-resistance and usually varnished laminates.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Very low voltages at very high currents are typical in the bars and end rings; high efficiency motors will often use cast copper to reduce the resistance in the rotor.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In operation, the squirrel-cage motor may be viewed as a transformer with a rotating secondary.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] When the rotor is not rotating in sync with the magnetic field, large rotor currents are induced; the large rotor currents magnetize the rotor and interact with the stator's magnetic fields to bring the rotor almost into synchronization with the stator's field.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] An unloaded squirrel-cage motor at rated no-load speed will consume electrical power only to maintain rotor speed against friction and resistance losses.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] As the mechanical load increases, so will the electrical load – the electrical load is inherently related to the mechanical load.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This is similar to a transformer, where the primary's electrical load is related to the secondary's electrical load.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This is why a squirrel-cage blower motor may cause household lights to dim upon starting, but does not dim the lights on startup when its fan belt (and therefore mechanical load) is removed.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Furthermore, a stalled squirrel-cage motor (overloaded or with a jammed shaft) will consume current limited only by circuit resistance as it attempts to start.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Unless something else limits the current (or cuts it off completely) overheating and destruction of the winding insulation is the likely outcome.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Many washing machines, dishwashers, larger standalone fans, compressors, etc. use some variant of a squirrel-cage motor.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] An alternate design, called the wound rotor motor, is used when variable speed is required.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In this case, the rotor has the same number of poles as the stator and the windings are made of wire, connected to slip rings on the shaft.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Carbon brushes connect the slip rings to a controller such as a variable resistor that allows changing the motor's slip rate.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In certain high-power variable-speed wound rotor drives, the slip-frequency energy is captured, rectified, and returned to the power supply through an inverter.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] With bidirectionally controlled power, the wound rotor becomes an active participant in the energy conversion process, with the wound rotor doubly fed configuration showing twice the power density.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Compared to squirrel cage rotors, wound rotor motors are expensive and require maintenance of the slip rings and brushes, but they were the standard form for variable speed control before the advent of compact power electronic devices.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Transistorized inverters with variable-frequency drive can now be used for speed control, and wound rotor motors are becoming less common.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Several methods of starting a polyphase motor are used.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Where a large inrush current and high starting torque can be permitted, the motor can be started across the line, by applying full line voltage to the terminals (direct-on-line, DOL).
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Where it is necessary to limit the starting inrush current (where the motor is large compared with the short-circuit capacity of the supply), the motor is started at reduced voltage using either series inductors, an autotransformer, thyristors, or other devices.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] A technique sometimes used is star-delta (YΔ) starting, where the motor coils are initially connected in star configuration for acceleration of the load, then switched to delta configuration when the load is up to speed.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This technique is more common in Europe than in North America.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Transistorized drives can directly vary the applied voltage as required by the starting characteristics of the motor and load.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This type of motor is becoming more common in traction applications such as locomotives, where it is known as the asynchronous traction motor.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] 2. a control-voltage (AC) winding in quadrature (i.e., 90 degrees phase shifted) with the main winding so as to produce a rotating magnetic field.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Reversing phase makes the motor reverse.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] An AC servo amplifier, a linear power amplifier, feeds the control winding.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The electrical resistance of the rotor is made high intentionally so that the speed–torque curve is fairly linear.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Two-phase servo motors are inherently high-speed, low-torque devices, heavily geared down to drive the load.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Single-phase motors do not have a unique rotating magnetic field like multi-phase motors.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The field alternates (reverses polarity) between pole pairs and can be viewed as two fields rotating in opposite directions.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] They require a secondary magnetic field that causes the rotor to move in a specific direction.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] After starting, the alternating stator field is in relative rotation with the rotor.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] A common single-phase motor is the shaded-pole motor and is used in devices requiring low starting torque, such as electric fans, small pumps, or small household appliances.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In this motor, small single-turn copper "shading coils" create the moving magnetic field.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Part of each pole is encircled by a copper coil or strap; the induced current in the strap opposes the change of flux through the coil.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This causes a time lag in the flux passing through the shading coil, so that the maximum field intensity moves higher across the pole face on each cycle.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This produces a low level rotating magnetic field which is large enough to turn both the rotor and its attached load.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] As the rotor picks up speed the torque builds up to its full level as the principal magnetic field is rotating relative to the rotating rotor.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] A **reversible shaded-pole motor** was made by Barber-Colman several decades ago.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] It had a single field coil, and two principal poles, each split halfway to create two pairs of poles.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Each of these four "half-poles" carried a coil, and the coils of diagonally opposite half-poles were connected to a pair of terminals.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] One terminal of each pair was common, so only three terminals were needed in all.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The motor would not start with the terminals open; connecting the common to one made the motor run one way, and connecting the common to the other made it run the other way.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] These motors were used in industrial and scientific devices.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] An unusual, **adjustable-speed**, low-torque shaded-pole motor could be found in traffic-light and advertising-lighting controllers.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The pole faces were parallel and relatively close to each other, with the disc centered between them, something like the disc in a watthour electricity meter.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Each pole face was split, and had a shading coil on one part; the shading coils were on the parts that faced each other.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Applying AC to the coil created a field that progressed in the gap between the poles.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The plane of the stator core was approximately tangential to an imaginary circle on the disc, so the travelling magnetic field dragged the disc and made it rotate.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The stator was mounted on a pivot so it could be positioned for the desired speed and then clamped in position.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Placing the poles nearer to the center of the disc made it run faster, and toward the edge, slower.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Another common single-phase AC motor is the *split-phase induction motor*, commonly used in major appliances such as air conditioners and clothes dryers.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Compared to the shaded pole motor, these motors provide much greater starting torque.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] A split-phase motor has a secondary startup winding that is 90 electrical degrees to the main winding, always centered directly between the poles of the main winding, and connected to the main winding by a set of electrical contacts.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The coils of this winding are wound with fewer turns of smaller wire than the main winding, so it has a lower inductance and higher resistance.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The position of the winding creates a small phase shift between the flux of the main winding and the flux of the starting winding, causing the rotor to rotate.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] When the speed of the motor is sufficient to overcome the inertia of the load, the contacts are opened automatically by a centrifugal switch or electric relay.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The direction of rotation is determined by the connection between the main winding and the start circuit.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In applications where the motor requires a fixed rotation, one end of the start circuit is permanently connected to the main winding, with the contacts making the connection at the other end.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] A capacitor start motor is a split-phase induction motor with a starting motor capacitor inserted in series with the startup winding, creating an LC circuit which produces a greater phase shift (and so, a much greater starting torque) than both split-phase and shaded pole motors.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This motor has a centrifugal switch which disconnects the capacitor once the motor has started.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This motor provides high starting torque.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This motor provides high starting torque and high efficiency.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] A resistance start motor is a split-phase induction motor with a starter inserted in series with the startup winding, creating reactance.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This added starter provides assistance in the starting and initial direction of rotation.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The start winding is made mainly of thin wire with fewer turns to make it high resistive and less inductive.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The main winding is made with thicker wire with larger number of turns which makes it less resistive and more inductive.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Another variation is the *permanent-split capacitor (or PSC) motor*.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Also known as a capacitor-run motor, this type of motor uses a non-polarized capacitor with a high voltage rating to generate an electrical phase shift between the run and start windings.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] PSC motors are the dominant type of split-phase motor in Europe and much of the world, but in North America, they are most frequently used in variable torque applications (like blowers, fans, and pumps) and other cases where variable speeds are desired.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] A capacitor with a relatively low capacitance, and relatively high voltage rating, is connected in series with the start winding and remains in the circuit during the entire run cycle.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Like other split-phase motors, the main winding is used with a smaller start winding, and rotation is changed by reversing the connection between the main winding and the start circuit, or by having polarity of main winding switched while start winding is always connected to a capacitor.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] There are significant differences, however; the use of a speed sensitive centrifugal switch requires that other split-phase motors must operate at, or very close to, full speed.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] PSC motors may operate within a wide range of speeds, much lower than the motor's electrical speed.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Also, for applications like automatic door openers that require the motor to reverse rotation often, the use of a mechanism requires that a motor must slow to a near stop before contact with the start winding is re-established.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The 'permanent' connection to the capacitor in a PSC motor means that changing rotation is instantaneous.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Three-phase motors can be converted to PSC motors by making common two windings and connecting the third via a capacitor to act as a start winding.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] However, the power rating needs to be at least 50% larger than for a comparable single-phase motor due to an unused winding.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The synchronous motor can also be used as an alternator.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Contemporary synchronous motors are frequently driven by solid state variable-frequency drives.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This greatly eases the problem of starting the massive rotor of a large synchronous motor.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Synchronous motors are occasionally used as traction motors; the TGV may be the best-known example of such use.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Huge numbers of three phase synchronous motors are now fitted to electric cars.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] They have a neodymium or other rare-earth permanent magnet.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] One use for this type of motor is its use in a power factor correction scheme.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] They are referred to as synchronous condensers.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This exploits a feature of the machine where it consumes power at a leading power factor when its rotor is over excited.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] It thus appears to the supply to be a capacitor, and could thus be used to correct the lagging power factor that is usually presented to the electric supply by inductive loads.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The excitation is adjusted until a near unity power factor is obtained (often automatically).
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Machines used for this purpose are easily identified as they have no shaft extensions.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Synchronous motors are valued in any case because their power factor is much better than that of induction motors, making them preferred for very high power applications.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Some of the largest AC motors are pumped-storage hydroelectricity generators that are operated as synchronous motors to pump water to a reservoir at a higher elevation for later use to generate electricity using the same machinery.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Six 500-megawatt generators are installed in the Bath County Pumped Storage Station in Virginia, USA.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] When pumping, each unit can produce 642,800 horsepower (479.3 megawatts).
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Small single-phase AC motors can also be designed with magnetized rotors (or several variations on that idea; see "Hysteresis synchronous motors" below).
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] If a conventional squirrel-cage rotor has flats ground on it to create salient poles and increase reluctance, it will start conventionally, but will run synchronously, although it can provide only a modest torque at synchronous speed.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Because inertia makes it difficult to instantly accelerate the rotor from stopped to synchronous speed, these motors normally require some sort of special feature to get started.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Some include a squirrel-cage structure to bring the rotor close to synchronous speed.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Various other designs use a small induction motor (which may share the same field coils and rotor as the synchronous motor) or a very light rotor with a one-way mechanism (to ensure that the rotor starts in the "forward" direction).
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In the latter instance, applying AC power creates chaotic (or seemingly chaotic) jumping movement back and forth; such a motor will always start, but lacking the anti-reversal mechanism, the direction it runs is unpredictable.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The Hammond organ tone generator used a non-self-starting synchronous motor (until comparatively recently), and had an auxiliary conventional shaded-pole starting motor.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] A spring-loaded auxiliary manual starting switch connected power to this second motor for a few seconds.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] These motors are relatively costly, and are used where exact speed (assuming an exact-frequency AC source) and rotation with low flutter (high-frequency variation in speed) are essential.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Applications included tape recorder capstan drives (the motor shaft could be the capstan), and, before the advent of crystal control, motion picture cameras and recorders.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Their distinguishing feature is their rotor, which is a smooth cylinder of a magnetic alloy that stays magnetized, but can be demagnetized fairly easily as well as re-magnetized with poles in a new location.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Hysteresis refers to how the magnetic flux in the metal lags behind the external magnetizing force; for instance, to demagnetize such a material, one could apply a magnetizing field of opposite polarity to that which originally magnetized the material.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] These motors have a stator like those of capacitor-run squirrel-cage induction motors.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] On startup, when slip decreases sufficiently, the rotor becomes magnetized by the stator's field, and the poles stay in place.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The motor then runs at synchronous speed as if the rotor were a permanent magnet.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] When stopped and restarted, the poles are likely to form at different locations.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] For a given design, torque at synchronous speed is only relatively modest, and the motor can run at below synchronous speed.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In simple words, it is lagging magnetic field behind magnetic flux.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] A universal motor is a design that can operate on either AC or DC power.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In universal motors the stator and rotor of a brushed DC motor are both wound and supplied from an external source, with the torque being a function of the rotor current times the stator current so reversing the current in both rotor and stator does not reverse the rotation.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Universal motors can run on AC as well as DC provided the frequency is not so high that the inductive reactance of the stator winding and eddy current losses become problems.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Nearly all universal motors are series-wound because their stators have relatively few turns, minimizing inductance.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Universal motors are compact, have high starting torque and can be varied in speed over a wide range with relatively simple controls such as rheostats and PWM choppers.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Compared with induction motors, universal motors do have some drawbacks inherent to their brushes and commutators: relatively high levels of electrical and acoustic noise, low reliability and more frequent required maintenance.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Universal motors are widely used in small home appliances and hand power tools.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Until the 1970s they dominated electric traction (electric, including diesel-electric railway and road vehicles); many traction power networks still use special low frequencies such as 16.7 and 25 Hz to overcome the aforementioned problems with losses and reactance.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Still widely used, universal traction motors have been increasingly displaced by polyphase AC induction and permanent magnet motors with variable-frequency drives made possible by modern power semiconductor devices.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Repulsion motors are wound-rotor single-phase AC motors that are a type of induction motor.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In a repulsion motor, the armature brushes are shorted together rather than connected in series with the field, as is done with universal motors.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] By transformer action, the stator induces currents in the rotor, which create torque by repulsion instead of attraction as in other motors.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Several types of repulsion motors have been manufactured, but the *repulsion-start induction-run* (RS-IR) motor has been used most frequently.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The RS-IR motor has a centrifugal switch that shorts all segments of the commutator so that the motor operates as an induction motor once it is close to full speed.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Some of these motors also lift the brushes out of contact with source voltage regulation.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Repulsion motors were developed before suitable motor starting capacitors were available, and few repulsion motors are sold as of 2005.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Where speed stability is important, some AC motors (such as some Papst motors) have the stator on the inside and the rotor on the outside to optimize inertia and cooling.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Exterior rotors are also common in ceiling fan motors.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] A conical rotor brake motor incorporates the brake as an integral part of the conical sliding rotor.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] When the motor is at rest, a spring acts on the sliding rotor and forces the brake ring against the brake cap in the motor, holding the rotor stationary.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] When the motor is energized, its magnetic field generates both an axial and a radial component.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The axial component overcomes the spring force, releasing the brake; while the radial component causes the rotor to turn.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] There is no additional brake control required.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The high starting torque and low inertia of the conical rotor brake motor has proven to be ideal for the demands of high cycle dynamic drives in applications since the motor was invented, designed and introduced over 50 years ago.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This type of motor configuration was first introduced in the US in 1963.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Single-speed or two speed motors are designed for coupling to gear motor system gearboxes.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Conical rotor brake motors are also used to power micro speed drives.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Motors of this type can also be found on overhead cranes and hoists.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The micro speed unit combines two motors and an intermediate gear reducer.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] These are used for applications where extreme mechanical positioning accuracy and high cycling capability are needed.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The micro speed unit combines a “main” conical rotor brake motor for rapid speed and a “micro” conical rotor brake motor for slow or positioning speed.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The intermediate gearbox allows a range of ratios, and motors of different speeds can be combined to produce high ratios between high and low speed.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Electronically commutated (EC) motors are electric motors powered by direct-current (DC) electricity and having electronic commutation systems, rather than mechanical commutators and brushes.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The current-to-torque and frequency-to-speed relationships of BLDC motors are linear.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] While the motor coils are powered by DC, power may be rectified from AC within the casing.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] These are two-phase induction motors with permanent magnets to retard the rotor so its speed is accurately proportional to the power passing through the meter.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The rotor is an aluminium-alloy disc, and currents induced into it react with the field from the stator.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] A split-phase watthour electricity meter has a stator with three coils facing the disc.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The magnetic circuit is completed by a C-shaped core of permeable iron.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The "voltage" coil above the disc is in parallel with the supply; its many turns have a high inductance/resistance ratio (Q) so its current and magnetic field are the time integral of the applied voltage, lagging it by 90 degrees.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This magnetic field passes down perpendicularly through the disc, inducing circular eddy currents in the plane of the disc centered on the field.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] These induced currents are proportional to the time derivative of the magnetic field, leading it by 90 degrees.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This puts the eddy currents in phase with the voltage applied to the voltage coil, just as the current induced in the secondary of a transformer with a resistive load is in phase with the voltage applied to its primary.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The eddy currents pass directly above the pole pieces of two "current" coils under the disc, each wound with a few turns of heavy-gauge wire whose inductive reactance is small compared to the load impedance.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] These coils connect the supply to the load, producing a magnetic field in phase with the load current.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] This field passes from the pole of one current coil up perpendicularly through the disc and back down through the disc to the pole of the other current coil, with a completed magnetic circuit back to the first current coil.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] As these fields cross the disc, they pass through the eddy currents induced in it by the voltage coil producing a Lorentz force on the disc mutually perpendicular to both.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Assuming power is flowing to the load, the flux from the left current coil crosses the disc upwards where the eddy current flows radially toward the center of the disc producing (by the right-hand rule) a torque driving the front of the disc to the right.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Similarly, the flux crosses down through the disc to the right current coil where the eddy current flows radially away from the disc center, again producing a torque driving the front of the disc to the right.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] When the AC polarity reverses, the eddy currents in the disc and the direction of the magnetic flux from the current coils both change, leaving the direction of the torque unchanged.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The torque is thus proportional to the instantaneous line voltage times the instantaneous load current, automatically correcting for power factor.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The disc is braked by a permanent magnet so that speed is proportional to torque and the disc mechanically integrates real power.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The mechanical dial on the meter reads disc rotations and the total net energy delivered to the load.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In a split-phase watthour meter the voltage coil is connected between the two "hot" (line) terminals (240 V in North America) and two separate current coils are connected between the corresponding line and load terminals.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] No connection to the system neutral is needed to correctly handle combined line-to-neutral and line-to-line loads.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Line-to-line loads draw the same current through both current coils and spin the meter twice as fast as a line-to-neutral load drawing the same current through only a single current coil, correctly registering the power drawn by the line-to-line load as twice that of the line-to-neutral load.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Other variations of the same design are used for polyphase (e.g., three-phase) power.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Representative are low-torque synchronous motors with a multi-pole hollow cylindrical magnet (internal poles) surrounding the stator structure.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The stator has one coil, coaxial with the shaft.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] At each end of the coil are a pair of circular plates with rectangular teeth on their edges, formed so they are parallel with the shaft.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] One of the pair of discs distributes the coil's flux directly, while the other receives flux that has passed through a common shading coil.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] The poles are rather narrow, and between the poles leading from one end of the coil are an identical set leading from the other end.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] In all, this creates a repeating sequence of four poles, unshaded alternating with shaded, that creates a circumferential traveling field to which the rotor's magnetic poles rapidly synchronize.
[src:manufacturing/ac-motor] Some stepping motors have a similar structure.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Most established academic disciplines have their own journals and other outlets for publication, although many academic journals are somewhat interdisciplinary, and publish work from several distinct fields or subfields.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] There is also a tendency for existing journals to divide into specialized sections as the field itself becomes more specialized.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Along with the variation in review and publication procedures, the kinds of publications that are accepted as contributions to knowledge or research differ greatly among fields and subfields.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] In the sciences, the desire for statistically significant results leads to publication bias.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Academic publishing is undergoing major changes as it makes the transition from the print to the electronic format.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Business models are different in the electronic environment.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Since the early 1990s, licensing of electronic resources, particularly journals, has been very common.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] An important trend, particularly with respect to journals in the sciences, is open access via the Internet.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] In open access publishing, a journal article is made available free for all on the web by the publisher at the time of publication.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Both open and closed journals are sometimes funded by the author paying an article processing charge, thereby shifting some fees from the reader to the researcher or their funder.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Many open or closed journals fund their operations without such fees and others use them in predatory publishing.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The Internet has facilitated open access self-archiving, in which authors themselves make a copy of their published articles available free for all on the web.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Some important results in mathematics have been published only on arXiv.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The *Journal des sçavans* (later spelled *Journal des savants*), established by Denis de Sallo, was the earliest academic journal published in Europe.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Its content included obituaries of famous men, church history, and legal reports.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The first issue appeared as a twelve-page quarto pamphlet on Monday, 5 January 1665, shortly before the first appearance of the *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society*, on 6 March 1665.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The publishing of academic journals has started in the 17th century, and expanded greatly in the 19th.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] At that time, the act of publishing academic inquiry was controversial and widely ridiculed.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] It was not at all unusual for a new discovery to be announced as a monograph, reserving priority for the discoverer, but indecipherable for anyone not in on the secret: both Isaac Newton and Leibniz used this approach.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Merton, a sociologist, found that 92% of cases of simultaneous discovery in the 17th century ended in dispute.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The number of disputes dropped to 72% in the 18th century, 59% by the latter half of the 19th century, and 33% by the first half of the 20th century.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The Royal Society was steadfast in its not-yet-popular belief that science could only move forward through a transparent and open exchange of ideas backed by experimental evidence.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Early scientific journals embraced several models: some were run by a single individual who exerted editorial control over the contents, often simply publishing extracts from colleagues' letters, while others employed a group decision-making process, more closely aligned to modern peer review.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] It was not until the middle of the 20th century that peer review became the standard.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The COVID-19 pandemic hijacked the entire world of basic and clinical science, with unprecedented shifts in funding priorities worldwide and a boom in medical publishing, accompanied by an unprecedented increase in the number of publications.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Preprint servers became much more popular during the pandemic, and the Covid situation also had an impact on traditional peer-review.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The pandemic has also deepened the concentration of science-publishing in Western countries.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Of the 720000 authors of papers published about COVID-19 before August 2021, nearly 270000 were from the US, the UK, Italy or Spain.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] In the 1960s and 1970s, commercial publishers began to selectively acquire "top-quality" journals that were previously published by nonprofit academic societies.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] When the commercial publishers raised the subscription prices significantly, they lost little of the market, due to the inelastic demand for these journals.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Although there are over 2,000 publishers, five for-profit companies (Reed Elsevier, Springer Science+Business Media, Wiley-Blackwell, Taylor & Francis, and SAGE) accounted for 50% of articles published in 2013.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] These factors have contributed to the "serials crisis" – total expenditures on serials increased 7.6% per year from 1986 to 2005, yet the number of serials purchased increased an average of only 1.9% per year.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Unlike most industries, in academic publishing the two most important inputs are provided "virtually free of charge".
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] These are the articles and the peer review process.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Publishers argue that they add value to the publishing process through support to the peer review group, including stipends, as well as through typesetting, printing, and web publishing.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Investment analysts, however, have been skeptical of the value added by for-profit publishers, as exemplified by a 2005 Deutsche Bank analysis which stated that "we believe the publisher adds relatively little value to the publishing process...
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Studies found the topic-specificity of scientific journals together with high impact factor expectations for career advancement some scientists have limited options in which journals to publish their work, resulting in limited competition in parts of academic publishing.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] A crisis in academic publishing is "widely perceived"; the apparent crisis has to do with the combined pressure of budget cuts at universities and increased costs for journals (the serials crisis).
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The university budget cuts have reduced library budgets and reduced subsidies to university-affiliated publishers.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The humanities have been particularly affected by the pressure on university publishers, which are less able to publish monographs when libraries can not afford to purchase them.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] For example, the ARL found that in "1986, libraries spent 44% of their budgets on books compared with 56% on journals; twelve years later, the ratio had skewed to 28% and 72%." Meanwhile, monographs are increasingly expected for tenure in the humanities.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] In 2002 the Modern Language Association expressed hope that electronic publishing would solve the issue.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] In 2009 and 2010, surveys and reports found that libraries faced continuing budget cuts, with one survey in 2009 finding that 36% of UK libraries had their budgets cut by 10% or more, compared to 29% with increased budgets.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] In the 2010s, libraries began more aggressive cost cutting with the leverage of open access and open data.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Data analysis with open source tools like Unpaywall Journals empowered library systems in reducing their subscription costs by 70% with the cancellation of the big deal with publishers like Elsevier.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Several models are being investigated, such as open publication models or adding community-oriented features.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] It is also considered that "Online scientific interaction outside the traditional journal space is becoming more and more important to academic communication".
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] In addition, experts have suggested measures to make the publication process more efficient in disseminating new and important findings by evaluating the worthiness of publication on the basis of the significance and novelty of the research finding.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] In academic publishing, a paper is an academic work that is usually published in an academic journal.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] It contains original research results or reviews existing results.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Such a paper, also called an article, will only be considered valid if it undergoes a process of peer review by one or more *referees* (who are academics in the same field) who check that the content of the paper is suitable for publication in the journal.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] A paper may undergo a series of reviews, revisions, and re-submissions before finally being accepted or rejected for publication.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] This process typically takes several months.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Next, there is often a delay of many months (or in some fields, over a year) before an accepted manuscript appears.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] This is particularly true for the most popular journals where the number of accepted articles often outnumbers the space for printing.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Due to this, many academics self-archive a 'preprint' or 'postprint' copy of their paper for free download from their personal or institutional website.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Some journals, particularly newer ones, are now published in electronic form only.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Paper journals are now generally made available in electronic form as well, both to individual subscribers, and to libraries.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Journals having this delayed availability are sometimes called delayed open access journals.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Ellison in 2011 reported that in economics the dramatic increase in opportunities to publish results online has led to a decline in the use of peer-reviewed articles.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Note: Law review is the generic term for a journal of legal scholarship in the United States, often operating by rules radically different from those for most other academic journals.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Peer review is a central concept for most academic publishing; other scholars in a field must find a work sufficiently high in quality for it to merit publication.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] A group of experts reviews the manuscript regarding its originality, correctness, and relevance.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] A secondary benefit of the process is an indirect guard against plagiarism since reviewers are usually familiar with the sources consulted by the author(s).
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The origins of routine peer review for submissions dates to 1752 when the Royal Society of London took over official responsibility for *Philosophical Transactions.* However, there were some earlier examples.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] While journal editors largely agree the system is essential to quality control in terms of rejecting poor quality work, there have been examples of important results that are turned down by one journal before being taken to others.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] "Confirmatory bias" is the unconscious tendency to accept reports which support the reviewer's views and to downplay those which do not.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Experimental studies show the problem exists in peer reviewing.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The possibility of rejections of papers is an important aspect in peer review.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The evaluation of quality of journals is based also on *rejection rate*.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The best journals have the highest rejection rates (around 90–95%).
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] American Psychological Association journals' rejection rates ranged "from a low of 35 per cent to a high of 85 per cent." The complement is called "acceptance rate".
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The process of academic publishing, which begins when authors submit a manuscript to a publisher, is divided into two distinct phases: peer review and production.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The process of peer review is organized by the journal editor and is complete when the content of the article, together with any associated images, data, and supplementary material are accepted for publication.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The peer review process is increasingly managed online, through the use of proprietary systems, commercial software packages, or open source and free software.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] A manuscript undergoes one or more rounds of review; after each round, the author(s) of the article modify their submission in line with the reviewers' comments; this process is repeated until the editor is satisfied and the work is accepted.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The production process, controlled by a production editor or publisher, then takes an article through copy editing, typesetting, inclusion in a specific issue of a journal, and then printing and online publication.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Academic copy editing seeks to ensure that an article conforms to the journal's house style, that all of the referencing and labelling is correct, and that the text is consistent and legible; often this work involves substantive editing and negotiating with the authors.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] Because the work of academic copy editors can overlap with that of authors' editors, editors employed by journal publishers often refer to themselves as "manuscript editors".
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] During this process, copyright is often transferred from the author to the publisher.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] In the late 20th century author-produced camera-ready copy has been replaced by electronic formats such as PDF.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The author will review and correct proofs at one or more stages in the production process.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] The proof correction cycle has historically been labour-intensive as handwritten comments by authors and editors are manually transcribed by a proof reader onto a clean version of the proof.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] In the early 21st century, this process was streamlined by the introduction of e-annotations in Microsoft Word, Adobe Acrobat, and other programs, but it still remained a time-consuming and error-prone process.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] At the end of this process, a final version of record is published.
[src:manufacturing/academic-paper] From time to time some published journal articles have been retracted for different reasons, including research misconduct.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] An **accounting network** or **accounting association** is a professional services network whose principal purpose is to provide members resources to assist the clients around the world and hence reduce the uncertainty by bringing together a greater number of resources to work on a problem.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The networks and associations operate independently of the independent members.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The largest accounting networks are known as the Big Four.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The **Big Four** are the four largest professional services networks in the world: Deloitte, EY, KPMG, and PwC.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The four are grouped because of their large sizes relative to their competitors, both in terms of revenue and workforce headcount; they are likewise considered comparable in their ability to provide consistent and reliable professional services to their clients.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Colloquially, their networks are considered *of parity* to those seeking careers in the services offered by these firms because of the frequency with which they engage with *Fortune* 500 companies.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The Big Four offer audit, assurance, taxation, management consulting, valuation, market research, actuarial, corporate finance, and legal services to their clients.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] A significant majority of the audits of public companies, as well as many audits of private companies, are conducted by these four networks.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Until the late 20th century, the market for these professional services was dominated by *eight* firms, which were accordingly nicknamed the *Big Eight*.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The Big Eight consisted of Arthur Andersen, Arthur Young, Coopers & Lybrand, Deloitte Haskins and Sells, Ernst & Whinney, Peat Marwick Mitchell, Price Waterhouse, and Touche Ross.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The Big Eight gradually evolved into the Big Four due to mergers between some of these firms, and culminated in the 2002 collapse of Arthur Andersen, leaving four networks dominating the market at the turn of the 21st century.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] In the United Kingdom in 2011, it was reported that the Big Four account for the audits of 99% of the companies in the FTSE 100 Index, and 96% of the companies in the FTSE 250 Index, an index of the leading mid-cap listing companies.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] This high level of industry concentration has caused concern among critics, and is the chief reason some notable people of business have expressed the desire for government bodies such as the UK's Competition & Markets Authority (CMA) to consider breaking up the Big Four.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] For over 70 years, the SEC has continually sought for greater coordination and consistent quality in audits everywhere in the world.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Networks were the logical model to address these requirements.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] They expanded outside of the United States since financial results had to be audited wherever a company conducted business.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] In the US, the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board's (PCAOB) regulations provide for inspection of non-United States firms.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Without a network with common standards and internal means of communications, conducting the required audits would not be possible.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] There were other profession-based factors which favored the growth of accounting networks.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] As a result of competition for the audit work, consolidation was inevitable.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] These include the fact that a network can establish a brand.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] A brand establishes the credibility of the network and allows the individual members to charge more.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Creating a brand is very difficult when all of the members of a network are providing essentially the same services.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Being a network member establishes that the firm is part of a large group.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Additionally, the larger the firm, the more likely it will be invited to render auditing engagements.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] A large organized network allows for spreading the costs to price competitively.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Ultimately, size is the only real means of differentiation that is readily available on accounting firms to assure clients that they can do international work.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Networks also reflect the clients’ needs for seamless worldwide services because they are more efficient and cost-effective.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] From the perspective of the accounting firm, a global regulated organization with consistently applied standards significantly reduced the risk.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] However, increasing the size of the networks can enhance legal liability risks and quality control issues that have not been resolved.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] With these factors in play, some networks continued to grow; others remained in a stasis position.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Individual members of networks began to offer other services related to accounting.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] These services included forensic accounting, business appraisals, employee benefits planning, strategic planning, and almost anything associated with financial parts of the client’s business.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The network’s structure easily accommodated these services and their geographical expansion.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] As the Big Eight consolidated to become Big Six, the Big Five and then the Big Four, new networks naturally developed to emulate them.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] BDO and Grant Thornton were the earliest followers.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Networks were then developed to serve mid-market companies and private businesses.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] New networks also sprang up as an extension of a single accounting firm in the same way the Big Eight were formed.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] New structures were created to further extend the networks.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The largest accounting networks adopted trade names that each member used.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The names of the original firms that became part of the networks were lost and replaced with trade names.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The perception was created that these networks were more than networks, but single entities rather than completely independent firms.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The result was that the Big Eight concept was established which separated the eight firms from all other accounting firms.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Another factor in the development of networks in accounting was the American Institute of Certified Public Accountants (AICPA)’s prohibition of advertising.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] While the largest firms indirectly advertised their services, the small firms complied with the rules and believed advertising to be unprofessional.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Additionally, midsize firms were de facto restricted from advertising simply because of limited budgets.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] They could not create a brand that was able to compete with the one established by the Big Eight.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The advertising restriction was lifted in the 1970s by the Federal Trade Commission.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] In the 1990s, the large accounting firms reached another ceiling in the services they made available to their clients.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Having reached their natural limit on growth with more than 90% of auditing for public companies, the Big 6 branched out to become multidisciplinary in legal, technology, and employment services.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Since the essential infrastructure was in place, it was thought to be relatively simple to incorporate other services into the existing network.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] As a network, it was natural to create independent entities in these other professions which themselves could be part of the network.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The method and structures varied from firm to firm.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] When the Big 6 began its expansion to the legal profession, it was met with fierce opposition from law firms and bar associations.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Commissions, panels and committees were established by legal and accounting firms to argue their positions.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] For more than five years the debate escalated.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] This movement ended abruptly with the fall of Arthur Andersen as a result of its association with Enron.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Sarbanes–Oxley followed, which effectively ended this trend.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Some international associations of independent firms, such as Alliott Group, now include law firms within the membership.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Accounting networks are adapting their operating models to address vicarious liability risks and clarify their legal structures.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Historically, many global accounting networks marketed themselves as unified entities; however, recent legal rulings have prompted these firms to distinguish between the global brand and the independent, locally incorporated member firms that actually deliver service.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Although accounting networks have been unsuccessful in several legal disputes, specific factual circumstances or procedural elements have mitigated their ultimate financial or legal liability.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The vicarious liability issues carry over into operations.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Regulations in the EU have been imposed that require the “networks” to define whether they are "associations" of independent firm or are more integrated networks operationally and financially.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Additional standards have been passed by the International Federation of Accountants, an independent organization representing the accounting industry, on distinguishing networks from associations.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The objectives of each are to provide the clients a level of understanding about the degree of integration with each other.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Examples of international associations of accounting firms include Alliott Group, GGI Global Alliance and Leading Edge Alliance.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Self-definition as a network or associations may determine if there is a conflict of interest.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] If the group is perceived as a network, it may be foreclosed from representation of clients because they cannot represent a competitor.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Association members would not be foreclosed from representation because the firms are perceived as independent by clients.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Accounting scandals have again focused on the fact that the Big Four has a near monopoly on audits of public companies.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] Networks are demanding regulations on auditing to require that auditors rotate and include the smaller networks in this rotation.
[src:manufacturing/accounting-network] The demands also request that mid-market firms be able to participate to break up the monopoly of the Big Four.
[src:manufacturing/ansi-isa-95] There are 5 parts of the ISA-95 standard.
[src:manufacturing/ansi-isa-95] The models help define boundaries between the enterprise systems and the control systems.
[src:manufacturing/ansi-isa-95] They help address questions like which tasks can be executed by which function and what information must be exchanged between applications.
[src:manufacturing/ansi-isa-95] Here is a Archived 2014-11-05 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:manufacturing/ansi-isa-95] Within production areas activities are executed and information is passed back and forth.
[src:manufacturing/ansi-isa-95] The standard provides reference models for production activities, quality activities, maintenance activities and inventory activities.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Manufacturing engineering is the field of engineering that designs and optimizes the **manufacturing process**, or the steps through which raw materials are transformed into a final product.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The manufacturing process begins with product design, and materials specification.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] These materials are then modified through manufacturing to become the desired product.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Contemporary manufacturing encompasses all intermediary stages involved in producing and integrating components of a product.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Some industries, such as semiconductor and steel manufacturers, use the term **fabrication** instead.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The manufacturing sector is closely connected with the engineering and industrial design industries.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The Modern English word *manufacture* is likely derived from the Middle French *manufacture* ("process of making") which itself originates from the Classical Latin *manū* ("hand") and the Middle French *facture* ("making").
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Alternatively, the English word may have been independently formed from the earlier English *manufacture* ("made by human hands") and *fracture*.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Its earliest usage in the English language was recorded in the mid-16th century to refer to the making of products by hand.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Human ancestors manufactured objects using stone and other tools long before the emergence of *Homo sapiens* about 200,000 years ago.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The earliest methods of stone tool making, known as the Oldowan "industry", date back to at least 2.3 million years ago, with the earliest direct evidence of tool usage found in Ethiopia within the Great Rift Valley, dating back to 2.5 million years ago.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] To manufacture a stone tool, a "core" of hard stone with specific flaking properties (such as flint) was struck with a hammerstone.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] This flaking produced sharp edges that could be used as tools, primarily in the form of choppers or scrapers.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] These tools greatly aided the early humans in their hunter-gatherer lifestyle to form other tools out of softer materials such as bone and wood.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The Middle Paleolithic, approximately 300,000 years ago, saw the introduction of the prepared-core technique, where multiple blades could be rapidly formed from a single core stone.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Pressure flaking, in which a wood, bone, or antler punch could be used to shape a stone very finely was developed during the Upper Paleolithic, beginning approximately 40,000 years ago.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] During the Neolithic period, polished stone tools were manufactured from a variety of hard rocks such as flint, jade, jadeite, and greenstone.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The polished axes were used alongside other stone tools including projectiles, knives, and scrapers, as well as tools manufactured from organic materials such as wood, bone, and antler.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Copper smelting is believed to have originated when the technology of pottery kiln allowed sufficiently high temperatures.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The concentration of various elements such as arsenic increases with depth in copper ore deposits and smelting of these ores yields arsenical bronze, which can be sufficiently work-hardened to be suitable for manufacturing tools.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Bronze is an alloy of copper with tin; the latter of which being found in relatively few deposits globally delayed true tin bronze from becoming widespread.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] During the Bronze Age, bronze was a major improvement over stone as a material for making tools, both because of its mechanical properties like strength and ductility and because it could be cast in molds to make intricately shaped objects.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Bronze significantly advanced shipbuilding technology with better tools and bronze nails, which replaced the old method of attaching boards of the hull with cord woven through drilled holes.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The Iron Age is conventionally defined by the widespread manufacturing of weapons and tools using iron and steel rather than bronze.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Iron smelting is more difficult than tin and copper smelting because smelted iron requires hot-working and can be melted only in specially designed furnaces.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The place and time for the discovery of iron smelting is not known, partly because of the difficulty of distinguishing metal extracted from nickel-containing ores from hot-worked meteoritic iron.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] During the growth of the ancient civilizations, many ancient technologies resulted from advances in manufacturing.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Several of the six classic simple machines were invented in Mesopotamia.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The Mesopotamians have been credited with the invention of the wheel.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The wheel and axle mechanism first appeared with the potter's wheel, invented in Mesopotamia (modern Iraq) during the 5th millennium BC.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Egyptian paper made from papyrus, as well as pottery, were mass-produced and exported throughout the Mediterranean basin.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Early construction techniques used by the Ancient Egyptians made use of bricks composed mainly of clay, sand, silt, and other minerals.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The Middle Ages witnessed new inventions, innovations in the ways of managing traditional means of production, and economic growth.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Papermaking, a 2nd-century Chinese technology, was carried to the Middle East when a group of Chinese papermakers were captured in the 8th century.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Papermaking technology was spread to Europe by the Umayyad conquest of Hispania.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] A paper mill was established in Sicily in the 12th century.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] In Europe the fiber to make pulp for making paper was obtained from linen and cotton rags.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Lynn Townsend White Jr. credited the spinning wheel with increasing the supply of rags, which led to cheap paper, which was a factor in the development of printing.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Due to the casting of cannon, the blast furnace came into widespread use in France in the mid 15th century.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The blast furnace had been used in China since the 4th century BC.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The stocking frame, which was invented in 1598, increased a knitter's number of knots per minute from 100 to 1000.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The Industrial Revolution was the transition to new manufacturing processes in Europe and the United States from 1760 to the 1830s.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] This transition included going from hand production methods to machines, new chemical manufacturing and iron production processes, the increasing use of steam power and water power, the development of machine tools and the rise of the mechanized factory system.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The Industrial Revolution also led to an unprecedented rise in the rate of population growth.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Textiles were the dominant industry of the Industrial Revolution in terms of employment, value of output and capital invested.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The textile industry was also the first to use modern production methods.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Rapid industrialization first began in Britain, starting with mechanized spinning in the 1780s, with high rates of growth in steam power and iron production occurring after 1800.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Mechanized textile production spread from Great Britain to continental Europe and the United States in the early 19th century, with important centres of textiles, iron and coal emerging in Belgium and the United States and later textiles in France.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] An economic recession occurred from the late 1830s to the early 1840s when the adoption of the Industrial Revolution's early innovations, such as mechanized spinning and weaving, slowed down and their markets matured.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Innovations developed late in the period, such as the increasing adoption of locomotives, steamboats and steamships, hot blast iron smelting and new technologies, such as the electrical telegraph, were widely introduced in the 1840s and 1850s, were not powerful enough to drive high rates of growth.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Rapid economic growth began to occur after 1870, springing from a new group of innovations in what has been called the Second Industrial Revolution.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] These innovations included new steel making processes, mass-production, assembly lines, electrical grid systems, the large-scale manufacture of machine tools and the use of increasingly advanced machinery in steam-powered factories.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Building on improvements in vacuum pumps and materials research, incandescent light bulbs became practical for general use in the late 1870s.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] This invention had a profound effect on the workplace because factories could now have second and third shift workers.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Shoe production was mechanized during the mid 19th century.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Mass production of sewing machines and agricultural machinery such as reapers occurred in the mid to late 19th century.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The mass production of bicycles started in the 1880s.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Steam-powered factories became widespread, although the conversion from water power to steam occurred in England earlier than in the U.S.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Electrification of factories, which had begun gradually in the 1890s after the introduction of the practical DC motor and the AC motor, was fastest between 1900 and 1930.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] This was aided by the establishment of electric utilities with central stations and the lowering of electricity prices from 1914 to 1917.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Electric motors allowed more flexibility in manufacturing and required less maintenance than line shafts and belts.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Many factories witnessed a 30% increase in output owing to the increasing shift to electric motors.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Electrification enabled modern mass production, and the biggest impact of early mass production was in the manufacturing of everyday items, such as at the Ball Brothers Glass Manufacturing Company, which electrified its mason jar plant in Muncie, Indiana, U.S. around 1900.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The new automated process used glass blowing machines to replace 210 craftsman glass blowers and helpers.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] A small electric truck was now used to handle 150 dozen bottles at a time whereas previously used hand trucks could only carry 6 dozen bottles at a time.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Electric mixers replaced men with shovels handling sand and other ingredients that were fed into the glass furnace.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] An electric overhead crane replaced 36 day laborers for moving heavy loads across the factory.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Mass production was popularized in the late 1910s and 1920s by Henry Ford's Ford Motor Company, which introduced electric motors to the then-well-known technique of chain or sequential production.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] All of these machine tools were arranged systematically in the production flow and some had special carriages for rolling heavy items into machining positions.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Production of the Ford Model T used 32,000 machine tools.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Lean manufacturing, also known as just-in-time manufacturing, was developed in Japan in the 1930s.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] It is a production method aimed primarily at reducing times within the production system as well as response times from suppliers and to customers.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] It was introduced in Australia in the 1950s by the British Motor Corporation (Australia) at its Victoria Park plant in Sydney, from where the idea later migrated to Toyota.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] News spread to western countries from Japan in 1977 in two English-language articles: one referred to the methodology as the "Ohno system", after Taiichi Ohno, who was instrumental in its development within Toyota.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The other article, by Toyota authors in an international journal, provided additional details.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Finally, those and other publicity were translated into implementations, beginning in 1980 and then quickly multiplying throughout the industry in the United States and other countries.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The concept of **world-class manufacturing** is associated with excellence in the manufacturing field.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The term has been promoted by author Richard J.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Schonberger, although Flynn *et al.* note that the term was initially used by R H Hayes and Steven C.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Wheelwright, before being taken up by Schonberger.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] In many manufacturing industries, production requires not only raw material supply chains but also the installation of large industrial machinery.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] According to a "traditional" view of manufacturing strategy, there are five key dimensions along which the performance of manufacturing can be assessed: cost, quality, dependability, flexibility and innovation.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] This view led to the theory of "trade offs" in manufacturing strategy.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Similarly, Elizabeth Haas wrote in 1987, about the delivery of value in manufacturing for customers in terms of "lower prices, greater service responsiveness or higher quality".
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Ken Platts and Mike Gregory devised a manufacturing audit scheme intended to support the process of formulating a manufacturing strategy.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] This was popularised in *Competitive Manufacturing: A Practical Approach to the Development of a Manufacturing Strategy* in 1998, whose publication was supported by the UK's Department of Trade and Industry.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] There are two main methods used for manufacturing control strategies, push manufacturing and pull manufacturing.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Push manufacturing involves manufacturing according to a forecast, and so batch processing and lot sizes are important considerations.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Pull manufacturing focusses on replenishment of goods, so what is produced is connected to the work demands of the next stage in a product's value chain.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Emerging technologies have offered new growth methods in advanced manufacturing employment opportunities, for example in the Manufacturing Belt in the United States.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Manufacturing provides important material support for national infrastructure and also for national defense.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] On the other hand, most manufacturing processes may involve significant social and environmental costs.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The clean-up costs of hazardous waste, for example, may outweigh the benefits of a product that creates it.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Hazardous materials may expose workers to health risks.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] These costs are now well known and there is effort to address them by improving efficiency, reducing waste, using industrial symbiosis, and eliminating harmful chemicals.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The negative costs of manufacturing can also be addressed legally.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Developed countries regulate manufacturing activity with labor laws and environmental laws.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Across the globe, manufacturers can be subject to regulations and pollution taxes to offset the environmental costs of manufacturing activities.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Labor unions and craft guilds have played a historic role in the negotiation of worker rights and wages.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Environment laws and labor protections that are available in developed nations may not be available in the third world.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Tort law and product liability impose additional costs on manufacturing.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] These are significant dynamics in the ongoing process, occurring over the last few decades, of manufacture-based industries relocating operations to "developing-world" economies where the costs of production are significantly lower than in "developed-world" economies.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] From a financial perspective, the goal of the manufacturing industry is mainly to achieve cost benefits per unit produced, which in turn leads to cost reductions in product prices for the market towards end customers.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] This relative cost reduction towards the market, is how manufacturing firms secure their profit margins.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The manufacturing sector is identified as a priority industry by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) within the National Occupational Research Agenda (NORA).
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] This designation facilitates the identification of occupational health and safety challenges and the development of intervention strategies.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Some local economic development plans address the location and labour supply needs of manufacturing industries and make provision for sites to be available and serviced.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] For example in the UK, Leeds City Council's local economic development plan refers to the needs of "modern manufacturing" in this regard.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Changes in production volumes and methods may at times require manufacturing relocation: heavy equipment such as presses, injection molding machines, and CNC tools may need to be moved during plant upgrades, facility relocations, or decommissioning projects.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] These processes involve specialized logistics, including rigging, tilt-and-load transport, forklifts, and oversize-load permitting.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] In North America, industry associations such as the Specialized Carriers & Rigging Association (SC&RA) provide safety standards and best practices for heavy transport and machinery moving.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Independent guides on machinery relocation planning offer strategies for minimizing downtime, such as phasing moves, off-hours relocation, buffer inventory, and detailed site assessments to maintain production continuity during equipment moving.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] In addition to general overviews, researchers have examined the features and factors affecting particular key aspects of manufacturing development.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] They have compared production and investment in a range of Western and non-Western countries and presented case studies of growth and performance in important individual industries and market-economic sectors.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Further, while U.S. manufacturing performs well compared to the rest of the U.S. economy, research shows that it performs poorly compared to manufacturing in other high-wage countries.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] A total of 3.2 million – one in six U.S. manufacturing jobs – have disappeared between 2000 and 2007.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] In the UK, EEF the manufacturers organisation has led calls for the UK economy to be rebalanced to rely less on financial services and has actively promoted the manufacturing agenda.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] According to the United Nations Industrial Development Organization (UNIDO), China is the manufacturer with the highest output worldwide in 2023, producing 28.7% of the total global manufacturing output, followed by the United States of America, Germany, Japan, and India.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] UNIDO also publishes a Competitive Industrial Performance (CIP) Index, which measures the competitive manufacturing ability of different nations.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The CIP Index combines a nation's gross manufacturing output with other factors like high-tech capability and the nation's impact on the world economy.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] Germany topped the 2020 CIP Index, followed by China, South Korea, the United States, and Japan.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] In 2023, the manufacturing industry in the United States accounted for 10.70% of the total national output, employing 8.41% of the workforce.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The total value of manufacturing output reached $2.5 trillion.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] In 2023, Germany's manufacturing output reached $844.93 billion, marking a 12.25% increase from 2022.
[src:manufacturing/manufacturing] The sector employed approximately 5.5 million people, accounting for around 20.8% of the workforce.
